const QUESTION_BANK = [["What is the purpose of a Power Supply Unit (PSU) in a PC?",["To convert DC power into AC power","To store backup electricity for later use","To convert AC power into regulated DC power for computer components","To increase the voltage supplied to the motherboard"],2,"A PSU is essential in a PC because it converts high-voltage AC power from a wall outlet into low-voltage DC power, which computer components need to function. Without this conversion, the motherboard, CPU, RAM, and other components would be unable to receive stable power.","Hardware"],["Why is electrostatic discharge (ESD) dangerous for PC components?",["It causes physical burns on the motherboard","It generates excessive heat, damaging capacitors","It can permanently damage sensitive electronic components like CPUs and RAM","It increases power efficiency"],2,"ESD occurs when static electricity discharges onto sensitive electronic components, potentially destroying delicate circuits inside a CPU, RAM, or motherboard. Even a discharge that is too small for humans to feel can cause microscopic damage that leads to system instability, crashes, or total hardware failure.","Operational Procedures"],["Which device helps protect a computer from power surges?",["Uninterruptible Power Supply (UPS)","Voltage Regulator","Surge Protector","All of the above"],3,"Each of these devices plays a critical role in protecting a PC from electrical fluctuations. A surge protector blocks voltage spikes that could damage sensitive components. A voltage regulator ensures that power remains at a steady level to avoid brownouts or power dips.","Hardware"],["Which PSU efficiency rating provides the highest energy efficiency?",["80 Plus Bronze","80 Plus Gold","80 Plus Platinum","80 Plus Titanium"],3,"The 80 Plus certification measures PSU efficiency. A Titanium-rated PSU is the most energy-efficient, with up to 94% efficiency at 50% load. This means it converts almost all incoming power into usable energy, minimizing heat production and reducing wasted electricity.","Hardware"],["What happens if you set a PSU to the incorrect voltage manually?",["The PC will run at half speed","The PSU could fail and potentially damage other components","The CPU will not boot but will remain undamaged","The PSU will adjust automatically"],1,"Many older PSUs have manual voltage selection switches that must be set correctly (e.g., 120V for North America, 240V for Europe). Selecting the wrong voltage can cause catastrophic failure. If set too low, the system may not receive enough power to boot.","Hardware"],["Which case type is most suitable for a high-performance workstation requiring multiple GPUs and extensive cooling?",["Mini-Tower","Full-Tower","Small Form Factor (SFF)","Desktop"],1,"Full-Tower cases are the largest type of chassis available and provide ample space for multiple GPUs, high-end cooling solutions, and extensive expansion options.","Hardware"],["What is one major advantage of choosing a Mid-Tower case over a Full-Tower case?",["More storage capacity","Greater portability and space efficiency","Supports only Mini-ITX motherboards","Provides the best thermal performance"],1,"While Full-Tower cases offer superior expandability, they take up a lot of space and can be difficult to move. Mid-Tower cases strike a balance between performance and practicality, supporting ATX motherboards while still being compact enough to fit comfortably under a desk.","Hardware"],["Why is cable management important in a computer case?",["It increases the speed of the CPU","It improves airflow and cooling efficiency","It prevents software from crashing","It reduces the number of power cables needed"],1,"Proper cable management helps keep internal components organized and prevents airflow blockages. Good cable routing ensures that fans and cooling systems can efficiently move air through the case, reducing the risk of overheating.","Hardware"],["Which case type is typically used in data centers and enterprise environments?",["Mid-Tower","Server/Rackmount","Mini-Tower","SFF"],1,"Server and rackmount cases are designed for data centers, enterprise applications, and home lab environments where multiple systems need to be housed efficiently.","Hardware"],["A student wants to build a compact gaming PC but still needs decent airflow. Which case type should they choose?",["Server/Rackmount","Full-Tower","Small Form Factor (SFF)","Horizontal/Desktop"],2,"SFF cases are designed for portability and space efficiency while still supporting high-performance components. Although they require careful hardware selection due to limited space, many SFF cases include good airflow solutions, such as strategically placed intake and exhaust fans or liquid cooling support.","Hardware"],["Which motherboard form factor typically provides the most PCIe expansion slots?",["Mini-ITX","Micro-ATX","ATX","E-ATX"],3,"Extended ATX (E-ATX) motherboards are larger than standard ATX boards and typically offer the most PCIe expansion slots. These boards are designed for high-performance systems like servers, workstations, or gaming rigs that require multiple GPUs or add-on cards.","Hardware"],["Which form factor is best suited for a compact, space-saving build?",["ATX","Mini-ITX","E-ATX","Micro-ATX"],1,"Mini-ITX is a small form factor motherboard designed for space-saving systems like compact desktops and home theater PCs. It typically includes one expansion slot and supports essential features in a very limited footprint.","Hardware"],["What is the primary advantage of choosing an ATX motherboard over a Micro-ATX motherboard?",["Lower cost","More expansion slots","Smaller size","Integrated graphics"],1,"An ATX motherboard offers more PCIe expansion slots than a Micro-ATX board, allowing for additional components such as graphics cards, sound cards, or RAID controllers. This makes it better suited for systems that require greater flexibility and upgradability.","Hardware"],["Which form factor is most used in business desktops due to its balance of size and expansion options?",["Pico-ITX","E-ATX","Micro-ATX","Mini-STX"],2,"Micro-ATX motherboards offer a strong balance between physical size and expansion capability, making them ideal for business desktops. They typically support up to four expansion slots while fitting in smaller cases, which reduces cost and saves space.","Hardware"],["Why might a user choose a Mini-STX motherboard instead of a Mini-ITX?",["To support multiple GPUs","To allow for CPU upgrades","To add more PCIe expansion cards","To install more RAM"],1,"Mini-STX motherboards are designed to be even smaller than Mini-ITX but still offer the advantage of a socketed CPU, which allows for processor upgrades. In contrast, many Mini-ITX systems, especially ultra-compact ones—use soldered CPUs with no upgrade path.","Hardware"],["Which front panel connector allows the computer to be turned on?",["HDD LED","Power Switch","Reset Switch","USB Header"],1,"The Power Switch connector (PWR_SW) is what allows the physical power button on the front of the case to communicate with the motherboard. When the button is pressed, it sends a signal through this connector that tells the motherboard to start the boot-up process.","Hardware"],["Which header should you use to connect front-panel USB 3.0 ports?",["USB 2.0","USB 3.0","USB Type-C","HD Audio"],1,"The USB 3.0 header connects the high-speed USB ports on the front of the case to the motherboard. These headers are typically blue and support much faster data transfer than older USB 2.0 ports.","Hardware"],["What is the purpose of the HD Audio header?",["To provide power to system fans","To connect front-panel USB ports","To enable sound through the front audio jacks","To connect RGB lighting"],2,"The HD Audio header connects the front-panel headphone and microphone ports to the motherboard. This allows users to plug in headsets or microphones directly into the case and use them without needing to reach behind the computer.","Hardware"],["Why is it important to check the motherboard’s user guide when connecting case headers?",["Different motherboards have different header layouts","The user guide provides troubleshooting tips","It helps identify correct pin orientations","All of the above"],3,"Every motherboard is designed a little differently. The user guide shows the exact location and layout of important headers like power, reset, and USB connectors. It also helps prevent mistakes like plugging cables in backwards or into the wrong pins, which can lead to system failures or even hardware damage.","Hardware"],["Which type of header allows for individually controlled RGB lighting effects?",["RGB","ARGB","SYS_FAN","HD Audio"],1,"ARGB (Addressable RGB) headers allow users to customize each LED light individually, meaning you can display multiple colors and effects at the same time across your lighting strips or fans. In contrast, standard RGB headers change all connected lights to the same color.","Hardware"],["Which part of older chipsets handled communication between the CPU and RAM?",["Southbridge","Northbridge","PCH","PCIe"],1,"The Northbridge was the part of the motherboard’s chipset that managed high- speed communication between the CPU, RAM, and graphics card. It played a key role in how fast data could move between those parts.","Hardware"],["What is the primary function of PCIe lanes?",["Transfer power to the CPU","Manage USB connections","Enable high-speed communication between the CPU and expansion cards","Store BIOS settings"],2,"PCIe lanes are like dedicated highways that allow expansion cards—such as graphics cards, SSDs, and network cards—to send and receive data quickly to and from the CPU. The more lanes a device has access to, the faster it can work.","Hardware"],["Which chipset feature allows users to increase CPU speed beyond its factory settings?",["RAID support","PCIe lane allocation","Overclocking","USB power management"],2,"Overclocking lets users push their CPU to run faster than the speed it was originally designed for. This can boost performance for gaming, video editing, or other demanding tasks. However, running the CPU faster creates more heat, so good cooling systems are necessary to keep the computer stable.","Hardware"],["Which type of chipset configuration is most commonly used in modern systems?",["Northbridge/Southbridge","Platform Controller Hub (PCH)","External chipset controllers","Southbridge-only architectures"],1,"Modern motherboards use a Platform Controller Hub (PCH), which replaces the older Northbridge/Southbridge design. The CPU now handles fast tasks (like memory access), while the PCH takes care of other functions, such as USB ports and storage. This setup improves speed and reduces bottlenecks between components.","Hardware"],["What happens if an NVMe SSD is installed in a shared PCIe slot?",["It disables the system’s CPU","The motherboard will refuse to boot","It may reduce bandwidth for other PCIe devices","It will overheat and damage the chipset"],2,"Some motherboard slots share PCIe lanes, meaning when one device—like an NVMe SSD—is installed, it can reduce how many lanes are available to other parts, like a graphics card or SATA port. This doesn’t break anything, but it can lower performance.","Hardware"],["Which storage connector offers the highest data transfer speeds?",["SATA","PCIe NVMe (M.2)","USB 3.0","IDE"],1,"While SATA (6 Gbps) is commonly used for SSDs and HDDs, PCIe NVMe M.2 drives can exceed 7,000 MB/s, making them significantly faster. USB 3.0 is used for external storage but is not as fast as NVMe, and IDE is an outdated technology.","Hardware"],["What is the primary function of a USB header on a motherboard?",["Connects external graphics cards","Powers internal cooling fans","Links front-panel USB ports to the motherboard","Controls system RGB lighting"],2,"USB headers allow the case’s front-panel USB ports to function by connecting them directly to the motherboard. This enables convenient access for USB drives, peripherals, and external storage.","Hardware"],["A motherboard includes a PCIe x16 slot. Which type of expansion card is most installed in this slot?",["Wi-Fi Adapter","Sound Card","Graphics Card (GPU)","Ethernet Card"],2,"The PCIe x16 slot is designed for high-bandwidth components, primarily graphics cards, which require maximum data transfer speeds for rendering images, video, and gaming. Smaller PCIe x1 slots are typically used for Wi-Fi adapters, sound cards, and Ethernet cards.","Hardware"],["What is the primary difference between an RGB and an ARGB header?",["RGB allows per-LED control, while ARGB does not.","ARGB allows per-LED control, while RGB does not.","RGB requires an external controller, but ARGB does not.","There is no difference; they are interchangeable."],1,"RGB headers provide a single color across all LEDs at the same time, while ARGB (Addressable RGB) headers allow individual LED control, enabling dynamic lighting effects like rainbow patterns and color cycling.","Hardware"],["Why is it important to check a motherboard's user manual before installing storage devices?",["To ensure that the correct connectors are used","To confirm compatibility with M.2 and SATA devices","To avoid installing an NVMe SSD in a SATA-only M.2 slot","All of the above"],3,"Motherboards have different slot configurations, and some M.2 slots only support SATA, while others support NVMe. Checking the manual ensures correct installation, proper connectivity, and full performance of storage devices.","Hardware"],["Which expansion slot is commonly used for high-performance graphics cards?",["PCIe x1","PCIe x4","PCIe x16","M.2"],2,"PCIe x16 slots provide the most bandwidth and data lanes, making them ideal for graphics cards (GPUs) that require high-speed connections to the CPU and memory. While other PCIe slots can host expansion cards, GPUs perform best in a full x16 slot.","Hardware"],["What happens if you install two PCIe devices in a motherboard that only has 16 PCIe lanes?",["Both devices will run at full speed.","Each device will get fewer PCIe lanes and may run slower.","Only one device will work at a time.","PCIe lanes do not affect performance."],1,"PCIe lanes are shared across expansion slots. If a motherboard has 16 PCIe lanes and you install two devices, the motherboard may split them into x8/x8 mode, meaning each device gets half the available bandwidth. This is common when using multiple GPUs or NVMe storage drives.","Hardware"],["Which expansion card type is commonly used for video capture and streaming?",["Sound card","Capture card","RAID controller","Network card"],1,"Capture cards allow computers to record and stream video from external sources, such as gaming consoles, cameras, and other PCs. These cards use PCIe slots to ensure high- speed data transfer, minimizing lag during streaming.","Hardware"],["What is the primary function of an M.2 Wi-Fi card?",["High-speed storage","Bluetooth and wireless networking","High-performance graphics processing","Audio enhancement"],1,"M.2 Wi-Fi/Bluetooth modules add wireless networking to a PC that doesn’t have built-in Wi-Fi. These small cards fit into M.2 Key E or A+E slots and often require external antenna connectors for better signal reception.","Networking"],["Why should users check their motherboard manual before installing an expansion card?",["To verify slot compatibility","To check bandwidth allocation","To ensure proper installation","All of the above e."],3,"Every motherboard has different slot layouts, bandwidth limits, and compatibility requirements. Checking the manual ensures: • The correct PCIe or M.2 slot is used. • The expansion card receives enough bandwidth. • The installation follows proper orientation and alignment.","Hardware"],["What is the primary function of BIOS or UEFI in a computer?",["Manage file storage","Initialize hardware and start the OS","Run system diagnostics after the OS loads","Improve internet connectivity"],1,"BIOS or UEFI is the first program that runs when a computer powers on. It checks and initializes all hardware—like the CPU, memory, and storage—before handing control over to the operating system. Without it, the computer wouldn’t know how to start up or communicate with its components.","Hardware"],["Which of the following is a key advantage of UEFI over traditional BIOS?",["UEFI supports only older operating systems","UEFI allows the use of larger hard drives and has better security features","UEFI runs only 16-bit applications","BIOS is faster than UEFI"],1,"UEFI supports drives larger than 2TB through GPT partitioning and includes modern security tools like Secure Boot and TPM (Trusted Platform Module). These features help protect against malware and improve system performance and compatibility with modern hardware.","Hardware"],["Which type of firmware should be used for a modern 64-bit operating system like Windows 11?",["Legacy BIOS","UEFI","16-bit DOS","EFI 1.0"],1,"UEFI is required for Windows 11 because it supports features like Secure Boot and TPM, which are not available in Legacy BIOS. It also works better with 64-bit systems, offers faster boot times, and supports more advanced hardware.","Operating Systems"],["A user wants to install Windows 7 (32-bit) on a modern UEFI motherboard. What setting might they need to enable?",["Secure Boot","Legacy Boot / Compatibility Support Module (CSM)","Fast Boot","Virtualization"],1,"Many older operating systems like 32-bit Windows 7 can’t boot in UEFI mode. Enabling Legacy Boot or CSM allows the motherboard to behave like an older BIOS system, making it compatible with older software and installation tools.","Hardware"],["A system is running Windows 10 on Legacy BIOS. The user wants to upgrade to Windows 11. What must they do first?",["Enable Secure Boot and TPM in BIOS","Convert the hard drive from MBR to GPT and switch to UEFI","Install a BIOS update to support Windows 11","Nothing, Windows 11 supports BIOS natively"],1,"Windows 11 requires a UEFI system and a hard drive formatted with the GPT (GUID Partition Table). Legacy BIOS uses MBR (Master Boot Record), which isn’t supported by Windows 11. Users need to convert the drive format and enable UEFI mode in BIOS settings before upgrading.","Operating Systems"],["Which CPU component handles floating-point calculations?",["ALU","FPU","Control Unit","L1 Cache"],1,"The FPU (Floating Point Unit) handles decimal-based operations, which are essential for tasks like 3D rendering, scientific computing, and simulations. The ALU handles only integer math and logical comparisons.","Hardware"],["What is the primary advantage of x64 CPUs over x86 CPUs?",["They use fewer instructions","They support more RAM and advanced processing","They are used only in mobile devices","They run older applications faster"],1,"x64 CPUs can address significantly more RAM than x86 and support 64-bit applications for better performance. They also maintain backward compatibility with most 32- bit software.","Hardware"],["Which CPU architecture is commonly found in mobile devices?",["x64","ARM","x86","CISC"],1,"ARM processors use a simplified instruction set that prioritizes power efficiency, making them ideal for mobile devices and tablets. They are common in smartphones and embedded systems.","Hardware"],["What is the primary function of CPU cache memory?",["Store long-term data","Speed up access to frequently used instructions","Transfer data between the CPU and GPU","Increase storage capacity"],1,"Cache memory stores data closer to the CPU than RAM, reducing wait times during processing. It helps bridge the speed gap between the CPU and main system memory.","Hardware"],["What is the difference between a process and a thread?",["A process is a single-core CPU, and a thread is a multicore CPU","A process is a running program, while a thread is a sub-task within a process","A process only works on ARM CPUs, while a thread works on x64 CPUs","There is no difference"],1,"Threads allow a program (process) to run multiple tasks concurrently within the same application. This improves efficiency, especially on multicore CPUs that can manage multiple threads at once.","Hardware"],["Which CPU socket type is commonly used by modern Intel processors?",["PGA","LGA","ZIF","AM4"],1,"LGA (Land Grid Array) is the socket type used by most modern Intel processors. In this design, the pins are located on the motherboard, and the CPU has flat contact points on its underside.","Hardware"],["What is the main advantage of a ZIF (Zero Insertion Force) socket?",["Provides a stronger connection","Prevents CPU overheating","Allows the CPU to be installed with minimal force","Uses compression to secure the CPU"],2,"A ZIF socket is designed so that the CPU can be placed into the socket without applying pressure. Once aligned correctly, a locking lever is used to secure the CPU.","Hardware"],["Where are multi-socket CPUs commonly found?",["Gaming laptops","Budget desktop PCs","Servers and data centers","Office workstations"],2,"Multi-socket systems allow for more than one CPU to be installed on the same motherboard. These setups are typically used in servers, data centers, and enterprise environments, where systems must handle heavy processing loads, such as hosting websites, cloud services, or performing complex simulations.","Hardware"],["Which RAM form factor is commonly used in laptops?",["DIMM","SO-DIMM","ECC RAM","Quad-Channel"],1,"SO-DIMM (Small Outline Dual In-line Memory Module) is the type of RAM used in laptops and compact systems due to its smaller size. It functions the same as standard desktop RAM but is designed to fit into tighter spaces. SO-DIMM is not interchangeable with DIMM, which is used in desktops.","Hardware"],["Which DDR version introduced the 288-pin DIMM?",["DDR2","DDR3","DDR4","DDR5"],2,"DDR4 memory introduced the use of 288-pin DIMM modules, which replaced the 240-pin layout used by DDR3. This change improved both data transfer speed and power efficiency. The different pin count and notch position also help prevent installation of incompatible modules.","Hardware"],["What happens if you install DDR4 RAM in a motherboard that only supports DDR3?",["It will work but run at lower speeds.","It will not fit due to different notch placement.","It will overheat and cause damage.","It will downgrade itself to DDR3 speeds."],1,"Each DDR generation has a unique notch position that prevents it from being inserted into an incompatible slot. DDR4 cannot be installed in a DDR3 motherboard because the physical connector is designed to block improper installations. This helps prevent electrical damage and confusion during upgrades.","Hardware"],["How do you check your installed RAM on a Windows PC?",["Device Manager","Task Manager → Performance Tab → Memory","Control Panel → RAM Settings","BIOS Setup"],1,"On Windows systems, Task Manager shows real-time details about your computer’s memory, including total capacity, speed, and DDR type. This tool is helpful for identifying whether your system has enough RAM or if an upgrade is needed. It also confirms whether the memory is being recognized properly by the system.","Hardware"],["What is a key advantage of DDR5 over previous generations?",["It uses more power.","It has fewer pins.","It supports higher speeds and bandwidth.","It is compatible with older motherboards."],2,"DDR5 memory offers significantly faster data transfer rates and greater bandwidth than DDR4, making it ideal for demanding tasks like gaming, video editing, and AI processing. It also uses slightly less power, improving efficiency in high-performance systems.","Hardware"],["Which type of RAM detects and corrects memory errors?",["Non-ECC RAM","Buffered RAM","ECC RAM","Registered RAM"],2,"ECC (Error-Correcting Code) RAM is designed to detect and automatically correct minor memory errors. This makes it ideal for servers, workstations, and systems where data accuracy and stability are critical.","Hardware"],["What is the primary benefit of dual-channel memory over single-channel memory?",["Increased memory bandwidth","Lower power consumption","Compatibility with older DDR generations","Increased RAM storage capacity"],0,"Dual-channel memory uses two RAM modules to double the communication bandwidth between the memory and the CPU. This leads to faster data transfers and better performance in multitasking, gaming, and professional applications. The system must have RAM installed in the correct slots to enable this mode.","Hardware"],["A PC builder is installing RAM but notices the system only recognizes half of the installed memory. What is the most likely cause?",["The RAM sticks are different brands","The RAM is installed in the wrong slots","The motherboard does not support DDR5","The CPU is overheating"],1,"Many motherboards require RAM to be installed in specific slots to enable dual- or quad-channel configurations. If the RAM sticks are placed incorrectly, the system may still boot, but it might only recognize part of the memory or run in single-channel mode. Always consult the motherboard manual for proper placement.","Hardware"],["How can you verify that RAM is running in dual-channel mode?",["Open Device Manager → Memory","Open Task Manager → Performance Tab → Memory","Run Windows Memory Diagnostic","Check the power supply"],1,"The Task Manager in Windows provides real-time memory usage details, including whether the system is using single- or dual-channel mode. This is an easy way to confirm if RAM has been installed properly and is performing at full potential without needing third-party tools.","Hardware"],["What should you check first if a newly installed RAM module is not detected?",["Reseat the RAM modules and check motherboard manual","Check the graphics card driver","Upgrade the CPU","Reinstall Windows"],0,"A common reason RAM isn't detected is that it's not fully seated in the slot, or it’s installed in the wrong configuration. Gently remove and reinstall the module, making sure it clicks into place. The motherboard manual will show the correct slots to use for optimal performance and compatibility.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["What is the primary purpose of Virtual RAM? T",["o act as a cache for the CPU","To store system backups","To extend available memory by using disk space","To increase graphics processing power"],2,"Virtual RAM, also known as swap space, allows the computer to use part of the hard drive or SSD as extra memory when physical RAM is full. This helps the system keep running instead of crashing, though it is much slower than real RAM.","Hardware"],["What is the name of the Virtual RAM file used by Windows?",["virtual.mem","pagefile.sys","swap.sys","vmcache.dat"],1,"Windows uses a file called pagefile.sys to handle virtual memory. When physical RAM runs out, data is temporarily moved to this file, giving the system more working space during heavy multitasking or large application use.","Hardware"],["Which of the following is a downside of relying too much on Virtual RAM?",["Increased CPU temperature","Slower overall system performance","Permanent data loss","Reduced Wi-Fi signal"],1,"Virtual RAM is stored on a hard drive or SSD, which is much slower than RAM. If the system uses it too often, it can cause noticeable lag or freezing, especially during demanding tasks like gaming or editing.","Hardware"],["On Linux and macOS, what is the equivalent of the Windows page file?",["Tempfs","Swap space","Systemd-mem","SysTemp space"],1,"Swap space in Linux and macOS serves the same purpose as Windows' pagefile—it provides virtual memory when RAM is full. This space can be a dedicated partition or a file and helps prevent crashes when memory is maxed out.","Operating Systems"],["When should a technician consider increasing the size of Virtual RAM?",["When the CPU is overheating","When the computer is frequently running out of disk space","When the system regularly freezes or slows under memory load","When installing a second GPU"],2,"If a system with limited physical RAM frequently slows down or becomes unresponsive, increasing virtual memory can help. This is especially useful for older computers or systems that run many programs at once.","Hardware"],["What is the primary purpose of the actuator arm in an HDD?",["Spins the platters","Moves the read/write heads","Stores magnetic data","Controls the power supply"],1,"The actuator arm is a mechanical component that moves the read/write heads back and forth across the surface of the spinning platters. This movement allows the heads to find the correct location to read or write data. It's like the needle on a record player, but much faster and more precise.","Hardware"],["What is a common spindle speed for desktop HDDs?",["5,400 RPM","7,200 RPM","10,000 RPM","15,000 RPM"],1,"7,200 revolutions per minute (RPM) is the standard speed for most desktop hard drives. This speed offers a good balance between performance and cost, making it ideal for everyday computing. Slower drives, like 5,400 RPM, are often used in laptops to save power.","Hardware"],["Why are HDDs more prone to failure than SSDs?",["HDDs have more storage capacity","HDDs have moving parts","HDDs require an external power source","HDDs are smaller in size"],1,"Hard drives have moving parts, including spinning platters and the actuator arm. These parts can wear out, break, or become misaligned over time, especially if the drive is dropped or used heavily. SSDs, on the other hand, have no moving parts, which makes them more durable and shock-resistant.","Hardware"],["What happens when an HDD’s platters stop spinning?",["Data access speeds increase","The drive stops functioning","The HDD switches to SSD mode","The read/write heads move faster"],1,"An HDD stores data on magnetic platters that must spin for the read/write heads to access data. If the platters stop spinning—due to motor failure or power loss, the drive becomes completely unusable. No spinning means no data movement, and therefore no functionality.","Hardware"],["How long do HDDs typically last before failure?",["6 months","1-3 years","3-7 years","10-15 years"],2,"Most HDDs last between 3 and 7 years, depending on how they’re used and how well they’re maintained. Factors like heat, dust, movement, and constant read/write activity can shorten a drive’s life. Regular backups are important because failure can happen suddenly with little warning.","Hardware"],["What is a primary advantage of SSDs over HDDs?",["Lower cost per gigabyte","Faster read/write speeds","Requires more power","Uses magnetic storage"],1,"SSDs use flash memory to store data, which allows them to access and transfer files much faster than HDDs that rely on spinning platters. This results in quicker boot times, faster application loading, and overall improved system responsiveness.","Hardware"],["What does TRIM do in an SSD?",["Prevents overheating","Clears unused data blocks","Increases NAND wear","Disables SSD caching"],1,"TRIM is a command that helps SSDs manage deleted data by telling the drive which blocks are no longer in use. This allows the SSD to clean up and prepare those blocks for future writes, keeping performance consistent over time.","Hardware"],["How does wear-leveling extend SSD lifespan?",["By moving frequently accessed data to HDD storage","By preventing data from being written to the same memory cells repeatedly","By cooling the SSD","By increasing NAND cell voltage"],1,"SSDs have a limited number of write cycles per memory cell. Wear-leveling spreads out write operations evenly across all cells, reducing the chance that any one area wears out prematurely. This helps maintain long-term reliability and performance.","Hardware"],["Which SSD interface provides the highest potential speeds?",["SATA","NVMe","USB","mSATA"],1,"NVMe (Non-Volatile Memory Express) drives use the PCIe interface, which allows for extremely high data transfer speeds compared to older interfaces like SATA. NVMe is ideal for demanding tasks like gaming, video editing, and large file transfers.","Hardware"],["Why do SSDs consume less power than HDDs?",["They use spinning platters more efficiently","They rely on magnetic fields to store data","They have no moving parts","They generate more heat, reducing power draw"],2,"SSDs are completely electronic, using memory chips instead of spinning disks or moving read/write heads. This makes them more energy-efficient, quieter, and better suited for battery-powered devices like laptops.","Hardware"],["Which USB version introduced speeds up to 5 Gbps?",["USB 2.0","USB 2.1","USB 3.0","USB4"],2,"USB 3.0 introduced SuperSpeed data transfer, capable of reaching up to 5 Gbps. This was a significant improvement over the much slower 480 Mbps limit of USB 2.0 and made USB 3.0 the go-to standard for high-speed external drives and peripherals.","Hardware"],["Which USB connector type is fully reversible?",["USB-A","USB Type-C","USB Micro-B","USB Mini-B"],1,"USB Type-C is fully reversible, meaning it can be plugged in either direction, which eliminates the frustration of trying to align the plug the \"right way up.\" It's now widely used due to its convenience and versatility across charging, data, and video functions.","Hardware"],["What is the maximum power output of USB Power Delivery (USB-PD)?",["10W","45W","60W","100W"],3,"USB Power Delivery allows supported USB-C ports to deliver up to 100 watts of power. This makes it possible to charge larger devices like laptops and monitors safely and efficiently through a single USB-C cable.","Hardware"],["Which of the following is NOT a USB feature?",["Hot-swapping","Backward compatibility","Wireless data transfer","Plug-and-play"],2,"USB is wired technology, meaning it uses cables to connect and transfer data between devices. Features like hot-swapping (plugging in without rebooting), plug-and-play, and backward compatibility are all part of USB’s design. For wireless transfer, technologies like Bluetooth, Wi-Fi, or NFC are used instead.","Hardware"],["What is a key advantage of Thunderbolt over standard USB-C?",["It supports external GPUs and daisy-chaining multiple devices","It charges devices at higher speeds","It is compatible with all USB ports","It is used for slow-speed peripherals"],0,"Thunderbolt uses the same USB-C connector but adds extra features like PCIe support, allowing connections to external GPUs, fast storage devices, and multiple 4K monitors. It also allows daisy-chaining, which means you can connect several devices in a row using one port.","Hardware"],["What is the primary purpose of cooling fans inside a computer case?",["To increase power efficiency","To improve internet speed","To maintain airflow and dissipate heat","To reduce noise levels"],2,"Cooling fans are designed to move cool air into the case and push hot air out. This airflow prevents internal components like the CPU, GPU, and power supply from overheating. Without proper cooling, parts can become too hot, leading to system instability, reduced performance, or hardware damage.","Hardware"],["What is the function of thermal paste?",["It helps secure the CPU to the motherboard","It improves heat transfer between the CPU and cooler","It prevents dust buildup on the heatsink","It allows the CPU to run without a cooler"],1,"Thermal paste fills microscopic gaps between the surface of the CPU and the cooler. These gaps can trap air, which is a poor conductor of heat. By using thermal paste, heat is transferred much more efficiently from the CPU to the cooler, helping keep temperatures under control.","Hardware"],["A user installs a liquid cooler but temperatures are still high. What should they check first?",["If the case fans are running","If the radiator fans are properly oriented","If the CPU supports overclocking","If the GPU is overheating"],1,"The direction of the radiator fans is critical for moving hot air away from the radiator and out of the case. If the fans are installed backward or incorrectly, they can work against airflow instead of helping it, causing poor cooling performance and high CPU temperatures.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["A technician installs a new CPU cooler, but the system begins to overheat shortly after. What is the most likely cause?",["The CPU fan is spinning too fast","The cooler is too powerful for the CPU","Thermal paste was not applied or was applied incorrectly","The power supply is overheating"],2,"Proper application of thermal paste is essential for effective heat transfer. If the paste is missing, spread unevenly, or too much was applied, it can cause hot spots on the CPU and prevent the cooler from working properly. This often leads to immediate overheating after installation.","Hardware"],["What is one advantage of a 4-pin fan connector compared to a 3-pin fan connector?",["It uses less power","It is quieter at all speeds","It supports Pulse Width Modulation (PWM) for speed control","It connects directly to the power supply"],2,"A 4-pin fan connector allows the motherboard to adjust fan speeds automatically based on system temperatures. This makes cooling more efficient by increasing airflow when needed and reducing fan noise when the system is cooler.","Hardware"],["During which step of the CompTIA six-step troubleshooting methodology would you document the solution for future reference?",["Establish a theory of probable cause","Verify full system functionality","Identify the problem","Document findings, actions, and outcomes"],3,"Documentation is the final step after you have successfully resolved the issue and confirmed that everything is working properly. Writing down the problem, your actions, and the final fix ensures that other technicians can solve similar issues faster in the future.","Operational Procedures"],["A customer reports that their prints are faded even after replacing the toner cartridge. What should the technician check next?",["Restart the print spooler","Update the printer firmware","Examine the fuser and transfer roller","Reinstall the printer driver"],2,"If replacing the toner cartridge doesn't fix faded prints, the next logical step is to check the fuser and transfer roller. These components physically bond the toner onto the paper, and if they are dirty or damaged, the toner may not stick properly, resulting in faded output.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["A user reports that their laptop will not boot. The screen is black, and there are no startup sounds. What should the technician check first?",["a) The boot order in the BIOS","The print spooler status","The AC adapter and power connection","System restore settings"],2,"If the laptop is completely unresponsive — no lights, no sounds, no screen activity — the most likely cause is a power problem, not a software issue. The first step should always be to check the AC adapter, the power cable, and the battery connection.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["What is the primary function of POST in the boot process?",["Load the operating system","Test hardware components","Manage user login","Display the BIOS menu"],1,"POST (Power-On Self-Test) is the very first step after a computer is powered on. It checks key hardware components like RAM, CPU, and storage to make sure they are working properly. If something fails during POST, the system will alert the user with error messages or beep codes before anything else happens.2.","Operating Systems"],["Which of the following is responsible for loading the operating system?",["BIOS/UEFI","Kernel","Bootloader","RAM"],2,"The bootloader is a small but critical program that takes over after the BIOS/UEFI finishes its checks. Its main job is to locate the operating system files on the hard drive or SSD and load them into memory.","Operating Systems"],["How does UEFI improve upon BIOS?",["Provides a graphical interface","Supports larger storage drives","Allows secure boot to prevent malware infections","All of the above"],3,"UEFI (Unified Extensible Firmware Interface) is a modern replacement for the older BIOS system. It adds important features like a graphical interface for easier navigation, support for hard drives larger than 2 TB, and Secure Boot to block malware from loading before the operating system starts.","Hardware"],["What happens if no bootable device is found?",["The computer automatically shuts down","The system displays an error message","The BIOS/UEFI loads the operating system","The computer continues to try random devices"],1,"If the system can't find a valid bootable device, like a hard drive with Windows or Linux installed, it stops and shows an error message. This message warns the user that the system cannot continue to load the operating system.","Operating Systems"],["What is the function of the kernel in the boot process?",["Runs POST","Manages hardware and system processes","Loads the bootloader","Displays the BIOS menu"],1,"The kernel is the core part of the operating system that takes control after the bootloader finishes its job. It manages the computer's hardware, loads necessary drivers, and starts essential system services. Without the kernel, the system would not be able to talk to devices like the hard drive, display, or keyboard.","Operating Systems"],["What is the primary function of an operating system?",["Running software only","Managing hardware and software","Providing internet access","Increasing processing speed"],1,"An operating system manages both the computer’s physical components (hardware) and the software programs running on it. It acts as the middle layer that allows software to communicate with the hardware. Without an operating system, a computer would not be able to function properly or run any applications.","Operating Systems"],["Which OS is known for being open-source and customizable?",["Windows","macOS","Linux","Chrome OS"],2,"Linux is considered an open-source operating system because anyone can view, modify, and share its source code. This makes it very flexible for users who want to customize their system’s behavior or appearance. In comparison, Windows and macOS keep their source code private and only allow limited changes by users.","Operating Systems"],["What does End-of-Life (EOL) mean for an OS?",["It stops working completely","It no longer receives security updates","It cannot install any software","It becomes faster"],1,"When an operating system reaches End-of-Life (EOL), it still runs but no longer receives important security patches and updates from the developer. This makes the system vulnerable to viruses, malware, and other security threats. Continuing to use an EOL system increases the risk of data loss or hacking.","Security"],["Which mobile OS is most widely used across different manufacturers?",["iOS","iPadOS","Android","macOS"],2,"Android is an open-source mobile operating system that is used by many different phone and tablet manufacturers like Samsung, Google, Motorola, and OnePlus. This wide adoption makes Android the most commonly used mobile OS in the world. In contrast, iOS and iPadOS are only available on Apple devices.","Mobile Devices"],["Why is it important to update your operating system?",["To install new applications","To change the user interface","To improve security and performance","To remove old files"],2,"Updating the operating system helps close security gaps that hackers might exploit, keeping the system safe from malware and attacks. Updates can also improve how fast and smoothly a system runs by fixing bugs and improving efficiency.","Operating Systems"],["What is the primary issue with file system compatibility?",["File formats change over time","Different OSs use different file systems","All OSs use the same file system","OSs don’t store files"],1,"Operating systems like Windows, macOS, and Linux each prefer their own file systems (such as NTFS, APFS, and ext4). This can create problems when trying to move data between different systems because not all OSs can fully read and write to every file system by default.","Operating Systems"],["What is a common solution for running Windows software on macOS or Linux?",["Reinstalling the OS","Using a virtual machine","Changing file systems","Modifying the registry"],1,"A virtual machine (VM) allows one operating system to run inside another, making it possible to use Windows-only programs even on macOS or Linux. The VM acts like a separate computer, isolated inside the existing system, providing flexibility without changing the main OS.","Operating Systems"],["Which network protocol is commonly used in Windows for file sharing?",["SMB","AFP","NFS","HTTP"],0,"SMB (Server Message Block) is the default network protocol used by Windows systems to share files, printers, and other resources across a network. It allows computers to access shared folders and devices easily.","Networking"],["What is one risk when transferring files between Linux and Windows systems?",["The file will be deleted automatically","The file's original permissions may not be preserved","The file format will corrupt","The system clock will reset"],1,"Linux and Windows manage file permissions differently, which can cause issues when transferring files between them. A file copied from Linux to Windows might lose its original security settings, potentially exposing sensitive information or restricting access incorrectly.","Operating Systems"],["Which file system is best for sharing large files between Windows and macOS without third-party tools?",["FAT32","NTFS","ext4","exFAT"],3,"exFAT is designed to handle large files (over 4 GB) and works natively on both Windows and macOS without needing extra drivers or software. Unlike FAT32, which has a file size limit, exFAT provides greater flexibility for transferring big files like videos or large project folders.","Operating Systems"],["Which file system is best for Windows system drives?",["exFAT","NTFS","FAT32","APFS"],1,"NTFS (New Technology File System) is specifically designed for Windows and supports features like file permissions, compression, large file sizes, and journaling, which helps protect against data corruption. It is the only file system that can be used to install and run the Windows operating system.","Operating Systems"],["Why is FAT32 still widely used for external storage devices?",["It has built-in encryption","It supports very large file sizes","It is compatible with multiple Oss","It is faster than all other file systems"],2,"FAT32 is one of the oldest and most widely supported file systems, making it a popular choice for USB drives and memory cards. It can be read and written by Windows, macOS, Linux, gaming consoles, and cameras without needing extra software.","Operating Systems"],["What is a major advantage of APFS over HFS+?",["It has better support for HDDs","It offers encryption, space sharing, and snapshots","It is the default file system for Windows","It has smaller file size limits"],1,"APFS (Apple File System) was designed to take advantage of the speed and features of SSDs and other flash storage used in modern Macs. It introduces advanced features like strong built-in encryption, the ability to share space across multiple volumes, and snapshots that allow the system to quickly save and restore data","Operating Systems"],["Which Linux file system is commonly used for desktop systems and offers journaling support?",["NTFS","XFS","ext4","FAT32"],2,"ext4 (Fourth Extended File System) is the most common file system for Linux desktop and server environments today. It includes journaling, which helps protect data by keeping a record of changes before they happen, reducing the risk of corruption during crashes or power failures.","Operating Systems"],["What should a technician do before formatting a storage device?",["Encrypt the drive","Convert it to NTFS","Adjust boot order in BIOS","Back up all important data"],3,"Formatting a drive completely erases everything stored on it, including files, programs, and partition information. Backing up data ensures that nothing important is lost during the process. It is always best practice to double-check and save critical files elsewhere before formatting any storage device.","Hardware"],["Which installation type removes all previous data and installs a fresh copy of the OS?",["Upgrade","Clean install","Image deployment","Repair installation"],1,"A clean install completely erases the existing operating system and all data on the drive before installing a fresh copy. This method is often used to fix serious system problems, remove viruses, or get rid of unwanted software (bloatware).","Operating Systems"],["Which boot method is commonly used in large organizations to install an OS over the network?",["USB boot","PXE boot","External drive boot","Multiboot"],1,"PXE boot (Preboot Execution Environment) allows a computer to boot from a network server rather than from a USB or internal drive. It’s useful in large organizations where multiple systems need to be set up quickly without using physical media. IT departments use PXE to streamline deployments across many machines.","Networking"],["What is a major limitation of MBR partitioning?",["Only supports one partition","Limited to 2TB drives and four primary partitions","Cannot be used on SSDs","Only works with Windows 11"],1,"MBR (Master Boot Record) is an older partitioning system that can only manage drives up to 2 terabytes and supports a maximum of four primary partitions. For modern computers and larger drives, this is very limiting.","Operating Systems"],["Which installation method allows fully automated OS deployment with no user interaction?",["Recovery partition","Image deployment","Zero-touch deployment","Repair installation"],2,"Zero-touch deployment installs the operating system automatically without needing the user to answer setup questions or click through prompts. It uses pre-configured scripts and tools like Microsoft MDT or WDS to handle the entire process.","Operating Systems"],["Why is it important to check driver compatibility before upgrading an OS?",["To speed up the installation process","To ensure connected hardware functions properly","To avoid having to reinstall the OS","To bypass user account setup"],1,"Drivers are software that allow the operating system to communicate with hardware like printers, graphics cards, and network adapters. If a driver isn't compatible with the new OS, that hardware may stop working or cause errors. Checking driver compatibility before upgrading helps avoid post-installation problems","Software Troubleshooting"],["Which Windows edition is best suited for large enterprises requiring advanced security and management tools?",["Windows 10 Home","Windows 11 Pro","Windows 10 Enterprise","Windows 11 S Mode"],2,"Windows 10 Enterprise is designed for large organizations that need powerful tools to manage devices, users, and data securely. It includes features like BitLocker encryption, Group Policy control, Windows Defender Advanced Threat Protection, and virtualization options.","Operating Systems"],["What is a major limitation of Windows S Mode?",["It doesn’t support external monitors","It restricts app installations to the Microsoft Store","It has no built-in security features","It lacks a Start Menu"],1,"Windows S Mode is focused on security and speed, especially for basic users or schools. However, it only allows apps to be installed from the Microsoft Store, which limits access to third-party applications. While this improves safety, it also reduces flexibility, which may not be ideal for more advanced users.","Operating Systems"],["Which Windows edition supports the Resilient File System (ReFS)?",["Windows 10 Home","Windows 11 Pro","Windows 10 Pro for Workstations","Windows 11 Home"],2,"ReFS (Resilient File System) is designed to protect data from corruption and support high-performance workloads, such as large-scale file servers and virtualization. It is available in advanced editions like Windows 10 Pro for Workstations and Enterprise. Home and standard Pro editions do not support ReFS natively.","Operating Systems"],["What is the key difference between an In-Place Upgrade and a Clean Install?",["An In-Place Upgrade keeps files and settings, while a Clean Install wipes everything","A Clean Install only works on SSDs","An In-Place Upgrade is required for Windows S Mode","A Clean Install does not require installation media"],0,"An In-Place Upgrade installs a new version of Windows without deleting personal files, apps, or settings. A Clean Install, on the other hand, completely erases the drive and installs a fresh copy of the OS. Clean installs are often used to fix deep system problems or start from scratch.","Operating Systems"],["Why is Trusted Platform Module (TPM) 2.0 required for Windows 11?",["It improves boot speed","It enhances security by encrypting sensitive data","It enables gaming features","It allows Windows to run on older hardware"],1,"TPM 2.0 is a small hardware chip that stores encrypted data like passwords and encryption keys. It adds an extra layer of security by protecting data at the hardware level, making it much harder for attackers to gain access to sensitive information.","Security"],["What’s the key difference between a domain and a workgroup?",["Domains are for corporate environments, workgroups are for personal networks.","Workgroups require a dedicated server.","Domains require all users to have the same password.","Workgroups do not allow file sharing."],0,"A domain is typically used in business or enterprise settings and allows for centralized user and device management using a server. In contrast, a workgroup is a simpler setup for home or small networks, where each computer manages its own settings and users.","Networking"],["What’s a VPN used for?",["Playing video games faster.","Securing data over a public network.","Replacing a firewall.","Speeding up Wi-Fi connections."],1,"A VPN (Virtual Private Network) encrypts internet traffic, creating a secure tunnel between the device and a remote server. This protects sensitive information, especially when using public Wi-Fi in places like airports or cafes. It helps keep data private and shields user activity from hackers or eavesdroppers.","Networking"],["Which network connection type offers the most reliable and stable performance?",["Wi-Fi","Cellular (WWAN)","Ethernet (wired)","Bluetooth tethering"],2,"Wired Ethernet connections are known for being the most stable and reliable because they are not affected by wireless interference. They also offer faster speeds and lower latency, making them ideal for tasks like gaming, streaming, or transferring large files.","Networking"],["Why would you set a connection as metered in Windows?",["To prioritize video streaming over other activities.","To limit background data usage and prevent excessive updates.","To increase download speeds.","To allow only administrator accounts to access the internet."],1,"Setting a connection as metered tells Windows to treat it like a limited data plan. This stops large downloads like automatic Windows updates from occurring in the background, helping users save data. It’s especially useful when connected to mobile hotspots or capped internet plans.","Operating Systems"],["What setting should you check if you can’t access shared files on a network?",["Bluetooth settings","Firewall and network discovery settings","Battery saver mode","VPN configuration"],1,"If shared files aren't showing up, one of the first things to check is whether network discovery is turned on. Additionally, the firewall may be blocking file-sharing services, preventing the system from seeing or communicating with other devices.","Networking"],["What does Windows Defender protect against?",["Power surges","Lost passwords","Viruses, malware, and cyber threats","Unwanted pop-up ads"],2,"Windows Defender (now called Microsoft Defender Antivirus) is a built-in security tool in Windows that protects against viruses, spyware, ransomware, and other harmful programs. It runs in the background and scans files in real time to stop threats before they cause damage.","Security"],["Why should you use a Standard User account instead of an Admin account for daily use?",["To improve internet speed","To limit malware’s ability to make system changes","To allow automatic software installation","To disable Windows updates"],1,"A Standard User account doesn’t have permission to install or modify system files without administrator approval. This helps protect the system from malware or unauthorized changes because harmful software can’t make major changes without a prompt. It adds an extra layer of security for everyday computer use.","Security"],["Which is the most secure login method?",["Password","PIN","Biometrics (Windows Hello Face/Fingerprint)","Security questions"],2,"Biometric logins use physical traits—like a fingerprint or facial recognition—to unlock a device. These are much harder to guess or steal than a password or PIN. Windows Hello makes logging in both secure and fast by requiring something unique to the individual.","Security"],["What does BitLocker do?",["Speeds up Windows startup","Encrypts your entire drive to prevent unauthorized access","Blocks malware from running","Cleans unnecessary files to free up space"],1,"BitLocker protects your data by encrypting the contents of the hard drive. If the computer is lost or stolen, the files remain unreadable unless the person has the correct encryption key. This is especially important for laptops or mobile devices used outside of secure environments.","Security"],["What happens if you disable UAC (User Account Control)?",["Windows becomes faster","Software updates are blocked","Malware can install programs without your permission","Your PC automatically logs into an admin account"],2,"User Account Control (UAC) asks for permission before allowing software to make major changes to your system. Disabling it removes that extra step, which makes it easier for malware to install itself silently. Keeping UAC enabled helps prevent unauthorized or harmful changes to the operating system.","Security"],["Which command would you use to see your computer’s IP address?",["dir","ipconfig","hostname","whoami"],1,"The ipconfig command displays important network information about your computer, such as its IP address, subnet mask, and default gateway. This is especially helpful when diagnosing network problems or checking connectivity. It’s one of the most commonly used tools for troubleshooting internet issues.","Networking"],["What does ping do?",["Checks if a website or device is reachable","Formats a disk","Shows network statistics","Displays your user profile"],0,"The ping command sends small test packets to another device or website to see if it responds. If a response is received, it confirms that the connection is working. It's often used to check internet connectivity or whether another computer is active on the network.","Networking"],["Which command deletes a file without sending it to the Recycle Bin?",["del","rm","erase","remove"],0,"The del command permanently deletes a file from the command line. Unlike deleting through File Explorer, it does not move the file to the Recycle Bin—the file is gone immediately. This makes it a powerful but potentially risky command if used without caution.","Operating Systems"],["What does chkdsk do?",["Formats a hard drive","Checks and fixes disk errors","Displays a list of files","Shows network settings"],1,"chkdsk (Check Disk) is a tool used to scan a hard drive for file system errors or bad sectors. It can also attempt to fix problems it finds, helping to prevent crashes or data loss. It’s useful when a drive is acting strange or files become inaccessible.","Hardware"],["Which command would you use to create a new folder?",["mkdir","touch","folder","cd"],0,"The mkdir (or md) command is used to create a new directory (folder) in the current location. It’s commonly used when organizing files in a command-line environment. For example, mkdir MyFolder creates a new folder named MyFolder.","Operating Systems"],["What is the core of the Linux operating system?",["GUI","Kernel","File System",""],1,"The kernel is the heart of the Linux operating system. It handles communication between the software and the hardware, such as memory, CPU, and devices. It also manages system resources, allowing multiple processes to run at the same time without conflict. Without the kernel, the OS wouldn't function.","Operating Systems"],["Which Linux distribution is best for beginners?",["Kali Linux","Arch Linux","Ubuntu","Fedora"],2,"Ubuntu is one of the most beginner-friendly Linux distributions. It has a user- friendly interface, strong community support, and wide compatibility with hardware and software. It's a great starting point for users who are new to Linux and want a system that \"just works\" out of the box.","Operating Systems"],["What is a key difference between Linux and Windows?",["Linux is closed-source, Windows is open-source","Linux allows complete customization, Windows does not","Windows is free, Linux is paid","Linux cannot run a graphical interface"],1,"One of Linux’s biggest strengths is that users can customize almost every aspect of the system—from the desktop environment to system behavior. In contrast, Windows restricts much of its interface and functionality to maintain consistency.","Operating Systems"],["Which of the following is NOT a Linux distribution?",["Fedora","Debian","CentOS","macOS ."],3,"macOS is Apple’s proprietary operating system and is not based on Linux. While macOS shares some Unix-like foundations, it is built on a different architecture (Darwin, based on BSD). Fedora, Debian, and CentOS are all examples of Linux distributions used for desktops, servers, or development.","Operating Systems"],["Which package manager is used by Ubuntu?",["dnf","apt","yum","pacman"],1,"apt (Advanced Package Tool) is the command-line package manager used by Ubuntu and other Debian-based Linux distributions. It allows users to install, update, and remove software quickly from official repositories. Commands like apt install and apt update make managing software simple and efficient.","Operating Systems"],["Which command shows your current directory?",["ls","pwd","cd","rm"],1,"The pwd command stands for \"print working directory.\" It shows the full path to your current location in the file system. This is helpful when you're navigating through multiple folders and want to confirm where you are. It does not list files—it only shows your current directory path.","Operating Systems"],["How do you create a new folder named Projects?",["touch Projects","mkdir Projects","ls Projects","cd Projects"],1,"The mkdir command stands for \"make directory.\" It’s used to create a new folder in your current location. For example, running mkdir Projects will create a folder named “Projects” in the current directory. This is useful for organizing files into separate folders.","Operating Systems"],["What does rm -r Folder do?",["Renames a folder","Deletes a folder and all its contents","Copies a folder to another location","Moves a folder to the trash"],1,"The rm command deletes files and folders. The -r flag stands for \"recursive,\" which means it deletes the folder and everything inside it, including subfolders and files. Be careful— this is a permanent deletion with no recovery from the Recycle Bin.","Operating Systems"],["Which command lists all files, including hidden ones?",["ls","ls -a","ls -l","ls -h"],1,"By default, the ls command lists only visible files. Adding the -a option (as in ls -a) shows all files, including hidden files that start with a dot (.), like .bashrc. Hidden files often store configuration settings and are not shown unless requested.","Operating Systems"],["How do you rename a file in Linux?",["rename file1.txt file2.txt","mv file1.txt file2.txt","cp file1.txt file2.txt","touch file1.txt file2.txt"],1,"The mv command stands for \"move,\" but it's also commonly used to rename files or folders. When you run mv file1.txt file2.txt, it changes the name from file1.txt to file2.txt. It doesn’t create a new file—just updates the existing file’s name.","Operating Systems"],["Which command opens a text file for editing?",["nano","find","grep","edit"],0,"nano is a beginner-friendly text editor. Explanation: The nano command opens a simple text editor directly in the terminal. It's commonly used to create or edit text files and is ideal for beginners due to its straightforward interface and on-screen shortcuts.","Operating Systems"],["What does grep -i 'error' logfile.txt do?",["Searches for \"ERROR\" only in uppercase","Searches for \"error\" (case-insensitive) in logfile.txt","Lists all files containing the word \"error\"","Deletes the word \"error\" from the file"],1,"The -i option in grep tells the command to ignore case sensitivity. This means it will match \"error\", \"Error\", \"ERROR\", or any other variation in capitalization found in logfile.txt.","Operating Systems"],["Which command finds a file named data.csv inside /home/user?",["nano data.csv","grep 'data.csv' /home/user","find /home/user -name 'data.csv'","ls /home/user | grep 'data.csv'"],2,"The find command is used to search through directories for files that match specific criteria. In this case, it searches the /home/user directory for a file named data.csv, making it a precise and efficient way to locate files by name.","Operating Systems"],["How do you search for files larger than 100MB?",["grep 100MB /","find / -size +100M","nano --size 100MB","ls -lh | grep 100MB"],1,"Using -size +100M with the find command tells it to look for files larger than 100 megabytes. This is useful when managing storage space or identifying large files that may need to be archived or deleted.","Operating Systems"],["Which command finds all .log files in /var/log/?",["grep '.log' /var/log/","find /var/log -type f -name '*.log'","nano /var/log/*.log","ls -l /var/log/ | grep '.log'"],1,"When searching for files, find /var/log -type f -name '*.log' returns only files (not directories) that end in .log. This combination of options is commonly used when scanning log directories for specific file types.","Operating Systems"],["Which command shows real-time system performance?",["htop","ls","ps","chmod"],0,"The htop command provides a live, interactive view of system resources such as CPU, memory, and running processes. It’s more user-friendly than the traditional top command because it includes color-coded graphs and allows you to scroll and sort easily. This makes it ideal for monitoring system performance in real time.","Operating Systems"],["How do you terminate a process with PID 1234?",["delete 1234","kill 1234","shutdown 1234","chmod -x 1234"],1,"The kill command sends a termination signal to a process using its PID (Process ID). This is useful when a program is unresponsive or consuming too many system resources. For example, kill 1234 would attempt to stop the process with the ID number 1234.","Operating Systems"],["What does chmod +x script.sh do?",["Deletes the script","Gives execute permissions","Changes the file owner","Stops the script from running"],1,"The +x flag adds execute permission to the file, allowing it to be run as a script. Without this permission, even if the file contains valid commands, the system won’t allow it to run directly. This is especially important when creating or running custom scripts in Linux.","Security"],["Which command changes file ownership?",["chown","chmod","killall","ps aux"],0,"The chown command stands for \"change ownership.\" It is used to assign a new owner or group to a file or directory. For example, sudo chown user file.txt changes the owner of file.txt to the specified user.","Operating Systems"],["How do you see all running processes?",["ps aux","top","htop","All of the above"],3,"Commands like ps aux, top, and htop all show currently running processes but in different formats. ps aux provides a snapshot in list form, top offers a dynamic, updating view, and htop adds color and easier navigation. Each is useful depending on the situation and user preference.","Operating Systems"],["Which file system is best suited for general-purpose Linux use?",["XFS","ext4","FAT32","NTFS"],1,"The ext4 file system is the default for many Linux distributions because it offers a good balance of speed, reliability, and flexibility. It supports large files, journaling for data recovery, and has wide compatibility across tools and utilities.","Operating Systems"],["Which file system is designed for handling large amounts of data efficiently?",["ext4","XFS","FAT32","exFAT"],1,"XFS is designed for high-performance environments, especially those working with large files like media archives, databases, and backups. It handles data allocation more efficiently than ext4 in some enterprise use cases, and it’s commonly used on servers where speed and scalability matter most.","Operating Systems"],["What does fsck do?",["Checks and repairs a filesystem","Mounts a USB drive","Lists available storage devices","Formats a partition"],0,"The fsck command stands for “file system check.” It scans a file system for errors like corrupted data blocks, missing files, or bad sectors, and attempts to fix them. This helps prevent data loss and system crashes, especially after improper shutdowns or hardware failures.","Operating Systems"],["Before running fsck, what must you do first?",["Unmount the filesystem","Delete the partition","Restart the system","Run chmod"],0,"Running fsck on a file system that is still mounted can lead to data corruption, because the file system might still be actively writing data. Unmounting ensures the system is not in use during the repair process, making it safe to scan and fix.","Operating Systems"],["Which command is used to attach a storage device to a directory?",["lsblk","mount","fsck","mkfs"],1,"The mount command tells the operating system to make a storage device, like a USB or hard drive, accessible through a directory. Once mounted, the system treats the device as part of the file system, allowing files to be read or written like any other folder.","Hardware"],["What is the correct command to unmount a storage device?",["umount /mnt/usb","unmount /mnt/usb","fsck /mnt/usb","detach /mnt/usb"],0,"The umount command safely disconnects a mounted storage device, ensuring that all data is properly saved before removal. Skipping this step can lead to data corruption, especially on USB drives or external storage.","Hardware"],["Which command lists all available storage devices and partitions?",["lsblk","fsck","chmod","grep"],0,"The lsblk command provides a visual layout of connected block devices, including hard drives, SSDs, USBs, and their partitions. It’s useful for identifying device names, mount points, and file system types before formatting or mounting.","Hardware"],["Which command allows you to switch users in Linux?",["sudo","su","switch","login"],1,"The su command stands for \"substitute user\" and is most often used to switch to the root user or another user account. When you run su, you're temporarily logging into a different account within the same terminal session.","Networking"],["Which package manager is used on Ubuntu?",["dnf","apt","yum","pkg"],1,"apt is the package manager used on Ubuntu and other Debian-based systems. It helps users install new programs, update existing ones, and remove software—all through simple commands in the terminal. Think of it like an app store for your system that works entirely from the command line.","Operating Systems"],["Which command checks network connectivity?",["ping","curl","dig","traceroute"],0,"The ping command checks if another computer or website is reachable by sending small packets of data and waiting for a reply. It also tells you how fast the response is, which helps you understand if there's a delay or issue with the connection. It's often the first tool used when troubleshooting network problems.","Networking"],["Which file contains the list of local user accounts in Linux?",["/etc/shadow","/etc/users","/etc/passwd","/etc/login"],2,"The /etc/passwd file holds important information about all local user accounts on the system, such as usernames, user IDs (UIDs), and default shells. While it used to contain password data too, that's now stored in a more secure file called /etc/shadow.","Operating Systems"],["What does the command sudo allow you to do?",["Switch to another user","Run a command with root privileges","Restart your terminal","Change file ownership"],1,"The sudo command stands for \"superuser do\" and allows a regular user to run commands with administrative (root) privileges. This is useful for tasks like installing software or changing system settings.","Networking"],["Which macOS feature allows you to view all open apps and desktops?",["Spotlight","Finder","Mission Control","Time Machine"],2,"Mission Control is a feature that gives you a bird’s-eye view of everything currently open on your Mac—including windows, full-screen apps, and additional desktops. It helps you switch between tasks quickly and stay organized. You can access it by pressing F3 or using a multi-touch gesture.","Mobile Devices"],["How do you quickly search for apps, files, or settings in macOS?",["Using Finder","Using Spotlight (Cmd + Space)","Opening System Preferences","Asking Siri"],1,"Spotlight is a powerful search tool built into macOS that helps you instantly find apps, documents, emails, and system settings. Just press Command + Space and start typing what you’re looking for. It’s one of the fastest ways to access anything on your Mac without using menus.","Operating Systems"],["What is Time Machine used for?",["Restoring deleted files","Searching for files","Managing windows","Changing security settings"],0,"Time Machine is macOS’s built-in backup tool that automatically saves copies of your files and system settings. If you accidentally delete a file or something goes wrong, you can “go back in time” to recover it. It’s especially helpful when troubleshooting or setting up a new device from an old backup.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["Where are most installed applications stored on macOS?",["/System","/Users","/Applications","/Library"],2,"Most apps you install on macOS are saved in the /Applications folder. This central location makes it easy to find, launch, and manage your software. You can access it quickly using Finder or by using Spotlight search.","Operating Systems"],["Which macOS feature syncs your files across all Apple devices?",["Finder","Keychain","iCloud","FileVault"],2,"iCloud is Apple’s cloud storage service that keeps your photos, documents, and other files updated across all your Apple devices. When you save something to iCloud, it becomes available on your iPhone, iPad, and other Macs signed in with the same Apple ID. It’s useful for backups and accessing your work from anywhere.","Mobile Devices"],["A technician receives a ticket stating that a user’s computer restarts every time it reaches the Windows logo. Which of the following is the most likely cause?",["Corrupt display driver","Incorrect time in BIOS","Boot loop caused by system file corruption","Dead CMOS battery"],2,"A boot loop that starts at or after the Windows logo is often caused by corrupted system files or failed updates. This issue can typically be resolved through Windows Recovery options like System Restore or Startup Repair.","Operating Systems"],["Which of the following actions would be the most appropriate first step if a computer powers on but displays a black screen after POST?",["Replace the power supply","Reset Windows","Test the hard drive using chkdsk","Boot with only the primary monitor connected"],3,"A black screen with no error after POST can indicate a display output issue, especially if multiple monitors are connected. The system may be sending video to the wrong display. Disconnecting secondary monitors helps determine if the output is going to the correct screen.","Software Troubleshooting"],["A user reports that their Mac won’t boot past the Apple logo. They recently installed a new external hard drive. What should the technician try first?",["Reinstall macOS","Disconnect the external hard drive and reboot","Run Disk Utility from Recovery Mode","Perform a PRAM reset"],1,"External drives can sometimes interfere with the boot sequence, especially if the Mac tries to boot from an unrecognized or unbootable device. Disconnecting the drive and rebooting allows the system to fall back to the internal drive as the primary boot source.","Hardware"],["What device sends data to all connected devices?",["Switch","Router","Hub","Bridge"],2,"A hub is a basic networking device that sends incoming data to all ports, regardless of which device actually needs the data. This can lead to unnecessary traffic and reduced network efficiency. Unlike a switch, which sends data only to the intended recipient, a hub does not filter or direct traffic intelligently.","Networking"],["Which network type is used for connecting smartwatches to phones?",["LAN","WAN","PAN","MAN"],2,"A Personal Area Network (PAN) is a very small network, typically used to connect devices within a few feet of each other—like a smartwatch and a phone via Bluetooth. It’s designed for short-range communication and often involves only one person’s devices.","Networking"],["What is the main advantage of a star topology?",["Simple to troubleshoot","Connects globally","Less expensive","High redundancy"],0,"In a star topology, all devices connect to a central switch or hub, making it easier to locate and isolate network problems. If one device or cable fails, the rest of the network stays operational, which simplifies both troubleshooting and maintenance. It also allows for easier expansion of the network.","Networking"],["What is a WAP used for?",["Encrypting data","Connecting wireless devices to a network","Storing user passwords","Powering off devices remotely"],1,"A Wireless Access Point (WAP) allows Wi-Fi-enabled devices—like phones, tablets, or laptops—to connect to a wired network without using cables. It acts as a bridge between the wireless signal and the network infrastructure, making it essential in environments that require flexible, wireless access.","Networking"],["A mesh topology is best known for:",["Central control","Low cost","Redundancy and fault tolerance","Easy setup"],2,"In a mesh topology, every device is connected to multiple others, creating multiple paths for data to travel. If one connection fails, data can still reach its destination using another route. This high level of redundancy makes mesh networks very reliable, especially in environments where uptime is critical.","Networking"],["Which internet connection type uses telephone lines and typically offers asymmetric speeds?",["Fiber","DSL","Satellite","Dial-up"],1,"DSL (Digital Subscriber Line) delivers internet over standard phone lines and is common in areas without cable or fiber. Download speeds are usually faster than upload speeds, making it ideal for web browsing and streaming but not heavy uploading.","Networking"],["A business in a remote area needs always-on internet access with consistent speed and minimal signal loss. Which type of service should they consider?",["Satellite","Leased line","Cable","Cellular"],1,"Leased lines provide dedicated, symmetric internet access with consistent performance, making them ideal for businesses with high reliability needs. Though expensive, they offer excellent uptime and performance regardless of location.","Networking"],["Which two types of internet are most commonly used for home broadband access in suburban areas?",["Dial-up and Satellite","DSL and Leased Line","Cable and Fiber","Cellular and SCADA"],2,"Cable and fiber connections offer high-speed broadband and are widely deployed in residential areas. Fiber offers the best performance, while cable remains a widely available and reliable option.","Networking"],["A user complains that their video calls lag and websites take longer to load during bad weather. What internet type are they most likely using?",["Fiber","Cable","Satellite","DSL"],2,"Satellite internet is sensitive to weather conditions, which can cause signal loss or increased latency. This makes it less reliable for real-time communication like video conferencing.","Networking"],["Which type of cable is most commonly used for Ethernet networking in modern LANs?",["Coaxial","Fiber optic","Twisted pair","HDMI"],2,"Twisted pair cables are the standard for modern Ethernet networks in homes and offices. These cables contain pairs of wires twisted together to reduce electromagnetic interference (EMI) from nearby devices and wiring.","Networking"],["A user is connecting a modem directly to a router. Which connector type would they most likely use?",["RJ-11","RJ-45","USB-C","SC"],1,"The RJ-45 connector is the standard interface for Ethernet cables, which are used to connect networking devices such as modems, routers, and switches. It looks similar to a phone connector but is wider and supports faster data speeds. This connector enables reliable, high-speed communication in wired networks.","Networking"],["You are asked to run Ethernet cable through an office building with heavy fluorescent lighting and multiple power sources. Which type of cable is most appropriate to minimize interference?",["Unshielded twisted pair (UTP)","Shielded twisted pair (STP)","Coaxial","HDMI"],1,"Shielded Twisted Pair (STP) cables have an extra layer of protective shielding around the twisted wire pairs, which helps block electromagnetic interference (EMI).","Networking"],["Which transport layer protocol provides reliable, connection-oriented communication?",["UDP","ICMP","TCP","SNMP"],2,"TCP (Transmission Control Protocol) is a connection-oriented protocol, meaning it sets up a reliable connection between devices before data is sent. It uses a process called the three-way handshake (SYN, SYN-ACK, ACK) to establish the connection, and then ensures all data is received correctly and in order.","Networking"],["A technician is troubleshooting a remote desktop connection issue. The user reports they cannot connect to their work computer from home using Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP). Which port should the technician check in the firewall settings to ensure RDP is allowed?",["22","53","3389","445"],2,"TCP Port 3389 allows a remote user to view and control a Windows desktop, as if they were sitting in front of it. Used by Remote Desktop Connection (built into Windows), If inbound connections on 3389 are blocked by a firewall (on the work computer or the network), RDP will fail faster than a caffeine-deprived help des","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["Which of the following services allows users to access websites and web applications through a browser?",["File server","VoIP server","Web server","Mail server"],2,"A web server hosts websites and delivers content via HTTP or HTTPS protocols. It enables users to access information or applications through a browser interface.","Virtualization and Cloud Computing"],["A company needs a central way to manage employee logins, apply security policies, and organize users into departments. Which type of server should they implement?",["DHCP server","Active Directory server","File server","VoIP server"],1,"Active Directory provides centralized user and resource management, allowing IT administrators to enforce policies, group permissions, and access control. It is a core service in most enterprise Windows environments.","Security"],["Which two of the following services would most likely be hosted by a file server?",["DNS","SMB","NFS","HTTP"],1,"SMB (Windows) and NFS (Linux) are both network protocols used by file servers to share and manage access to files across a network. DNS and HTTP are unrelated to direct file storage and sharing. 5 A startup wants to reduce its physical hardware footprint and increase flexibility for running test environments.","Networking"],["What is the primary role of DHCP in a network?",["Resolving domain names to IP addresses","Assigning IP addresses dynamically to devices","Encrypting network traffic for secure connections","Segmenting networks into smaller subnets"],1,"DHCP (Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol) is responsible for automatically assigning network settings like IP addresses, subnet masks, and default gateways to devices on the network. This means users don’t need to manually enter IP information.","Networking"],["You’re troubleshooting a workstation that cannot access the internet. Running ipconfig shows the following IP address: 169.254.12.45. What is the most likely cause of this issue?",["The computer has been manually assigned a static IP.","The DHCP server is unreachable or not working.","The DNS server is misconfigured.","The subnet mask is incorrect."],1,"An IP address starting with 169.254.x.x means the computer assigned itself an address using APIPA (Automatic Private IP Addressing) because it didn’t hear back from a DHCP server. This address allows local communication only, but not internet access.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["Which of the following best describes a VLAN?",["A network that encrypts data for secure remote access","A logical segmentation of a physical network to improve security and performance","A protocol used to dynamically assign IP addresses","A high-speed internet connection method"],1,"A VLAN (Virtual Local Area Network) allows network administrators to separate users or departments on the same physical network into isolated virtual networks. This keeps unrelated traffic from interfering with other parts of the network and improves both security and performance.","Networking"],["What is the primary difference between IPv4 and IPv6?",["IPv4 uses 128-bit addresses, while IPv6 uses 32-bit addresses","IPv6 supports more unique addresses than IPv4","IPv4 is only used in local networks","IPv6 requires manual configuration"],1,"IPv4 has about 4.3 billion possible addresses, which is not enough for the growing number of internet-connected devices. IPv6 solves this by offering trillions of unique addresses, making it more future-proof. It also includes improvements in routing and security features.","Networking"],["Which wireless encryption protocol provides the strongest security?",["WEP","WPA","WPA2 with TKIP","WPA3"],3,"WPA3 is the most secure wireless encryption protocol, offering stronger encryption, protection against brute-force attacks, and forward secrecy. WEP and WPA are outdated and vulnerable to hacking, while WPA2️ is still secure but lacks some of WPA3️’s advanced protections.","Security"],["An IT technician is setting up a secure Wi-Fi network for a corporate office. Employees need to authenticate with unique usernames and passwords. Which security mode should they use?",["WPA2-Personal (PSK)","WEP","WPA2-Enterprise (EAP/RADIUS)","Open Wi-Fi with MAC filtering"],2,"WPA2-Enterprise uses a RADIUS server for authentication, allowing individual usernames and passwords instead of a single shared key. This is the best option for businesses needing strong security and user authentication management. WPA2-Personal (PSK) is fine for small networks, but not for corporate environments.","Networking"],["Which mobile network technology offers the fastest speeds and lowest latency?",["3G","4G LTE","5G","Bluetooth"],2,"5G networks provide ultra-fast speeds (up to 10 Gbps) and low latency, making them ideal for high-performance applications like smart cities, IoT, and cloud computing. 3G and 4G LTE are slower, and Bluetooth is used for short-range connectivity, not mobile networks.","Networking"],["Which of the following functions does a typical SOHO networking device perform?",["Only routing network traffic","Only providing Wi-Fi connectivity","Routing, wireless access, firewall, and DHCP services","Managing cloud-based applications directly"],2,"Most SOHO networking devices are multi-functional, acting as a router, wireless access point (WAP), Ethernet switch, firewall, and DHCP server in a single unit. Unlike enterprise networks, which use separate devices for each function, SOHO networks consolidate these into one device for convenience and simplicity.","Networking"],["An IT technician needs to configure port forwarding on a SOHO router to allow remote access to a security camera. What steps should they take?",["Assign a static IP to the security camera, configure port forwarding in the router, and test external access","Enable DHCP on the security camera and allow the router to assign an IP dynamically","Open all ports on the firewall to ensure the security camera receives external traffic","Enable MAC filtering to allow only authorized IP addresses to access the security camera"],0,"For port forwarding to work properly, the security camera must have a static IP address so the router always directs external traffic to the correct device. The specific port used by the camera (e.g., 554 for RTSP or 8080 for web access) must be forwarded in the router's settings.","Networking"],["Which protocol is commonly used to monitor and manage network devices such as switches and routers?",["DNS","SNMP","SMTP","FTP"],1,"SNMP (Simple Network Management Protocol) is used to collect information from network devices like switches, routers, and access points. It allows network tools to monitor device health, track performance metrics (such as CPU or memory usage), and generate alerts if something goes wrong.","Networking"],["An IT administrator notices that certain devices on the network are using an excessive amount of bandwidth, slowing down business-critical applications. Which monitoring tool should they use to analyze traffic flow and identify the source of congestion?",["Syslog","NetFlow","Ping","DHCP"],1,"NetFlow is a traffic analysis tool that shows how data flows through the network and which devices or applications are using the most bandwidth. It provides visibility into traffic patterns, allowing administrators to pinpoint congestion sources and adjust settings or policies to improve performance.","Networking"],["A company's network monitoring tool sends an automated alert indicating that a critical switch is experiencing high packet loss. Why is this type of alert important for IT teams?",["It helps them respond before users experience network issues","It ensures the network runs on outdated firmware","It eliminates the need for network monitoring altogether","It prevents future firmware updates from being installed"],0,"Automated alerts allow teams to act on a problem before users notice slowdowns or outages. High packet loss can lead to dropped connections, slow performance, or service disruptions, so early warnings give time to investigate and fix the issue.","Networking"],["A user reports that their video calls are choppy, with delayed responses and audio that cuts in and out. Which two network issues are most likely contributing to this problem?",["Low bandwidth and intermittent Wi-Fi signal","DNS misconfiguration and packet fragmentation","Jitter and latency","Port blocking and firewall timeouts"],2,"Jitter and latency affect the consistency and timing of packet delivery, which is especially noticeable during real-time communications like VoIP or video conferencing. These issues often result in choppy audio, lag, or dropped segments of the conversation.","Networking"],["Which tool or step should a technician use to confirm intermittent packet loss between a user's system and the default gateway?",["Reboot the DHCP server","Change the MAC address","Use the ping command","Replace the Ethernet cable with a longer one"],2,"The ping command is a simple and effective tool for testing connectivity and identifying dropped packets. Running continuous pings can reveal patterns in intermittent loss.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["A user complains that they are connected to the network but cannot access any websites. You verify that the local network is working. What is the most likely cause?",["DHCP server is down","DNS server is misconfigured or unavailable","Wi-Fi password is incorrect","IP conflict with another device"],1,"If a device can connect to the local network but can't reach websites, a DNS failure is a likely cause. DNS translates web addresses into IP addresses, so without it, the browser cannot find the requested sites.","Networking"],["Which of the following statements BEST describes the advantage of a hybrid cloud model?",["It offers the lowest cost and simplest setup","It combines the control of private clouds with the scalability of public clouds","It is only used by government and research institutions","It eliminates the need for public cloud services altogether"],1,"A hybrid cloud combines a private cloud, which keeps sensitive data and critical workloads under direct organizational control, with a public cloud, which provides on-demand scalability and lower infrastructure costs. Businesses can burst to public cloud resources during demand spikes while keeping core systems private.","Virtualization and Cloud Computing"],["Scenario: A company shares a cloud storage folder with unrestricted public access. A month later, customer data is discovered on a public forum. What likely caused this breach?",["A denial-of-service (DDoS) attack occurred","A failure in the cloud provider’s encryption service","Misconfigured cloud storage permissions","A power outage in the data center"],2,"When a cloud storage folder or bucket is left with unrestricted public access, anyone with the link, or who finds it through scanning, can view its contents. This is one of the most common real-world causes of cloud data breaches and is prevented by properly configuring access permissions and regularly auditing sharing settings.","Virtualization and Cloud Computing"],["What is one major benefit of multitenancy in cloud environments?",["It gives each customer a dedicated server with no shared resources","It reduces costs by allowing multiple users to share the same infrastructure","It eliminates the need for encryption","It restricts scalability and flexibility"],1,"Multitenancy allows a single set of cloud infrastructure to serve many customers at once, with each tenant's data logically isolated but the underlying hardware and resources shared. This shared-resource model is what allows cloud providers to offer lower costs than dedicated, single-tenant infrastructure.","Virtualization and Cloud Computing"],["What is the first step before installing a new application?",["Click \"Next\" until installation completes","Check system requirements","Disable security settings","Restart the computer"],1,"Before installing software, it’s important to check whether your computer meets the minimum and recommended system requirements. This helps ensure the application will run correctly and prevents issues like failed installations, crashes, or slow performance.","Software Troubleshooting"],["Why might a high-performance game run poorly on a computer with an integrated graphics card?",["Integrated graphics share system RAM and have lower processing power","The CPU handles all graphics processing","Integrated graphics always outperform dedicated GPUs","The operating system does not support graphics acceleration"],0,"Integrated graphics use the system’s RAM instead of having their own dedicated memory (VRAM), which reduces overall performance. These types of GPUs are good for basic tasks but struggle with demanding applications like modern video games. A dedicated graphics card is better suited for high-performance graphics needs.","Hardware"],["Which method is commonly used in businesses to install applications on multiple computers at once?",["Image deployment","Downloading an installer on each machine manually","Using a USB drive for each installation","Waiting for employees to install software themselves"],0,"Image deployment is a process used by IT departments to clone a computer setup—including software, settings, and system configurations—and apply it across many machines at once. This saves time, ensures consistency, and prevents errors that may occur with manual installations.","Software Troubleshooting"],["What is one of the biggest risks of running out of storage space during an installation?",["The system will automatically allocate cloud storage","The installation may fail, and the system may slow down","The application will continue installing but function at half speed","The software will install onto external drives by default"],1,"When your device runs out of available storage, the software may fail to install properly or leave behind incomplete files. Low disk space can also reduce system performance, causing your device to slow down or freeze. It’s best to clear space before starting any large installation.","Software Troubleshooting"],["What should you check if an application fails to launch after installation?",["Verify OS compatibility and update drivers","Reinstall the operating system","Close all other running applications","Change the system theme"],0,"Some applications won't run unless they are compatible with your operating system version and have the correct hardware drivers installed. Updating your graphics, audio, and chipset drivers, and checking the software's requirements can often fix launch issues.","Hardware"],["What is the main difference between web-based and hybrid cloud applications?",["Web-based apps must be downloaded, hybrid apps run in a browser","Hybrid apps require no internet connection, web apps do","Web-based apps run in a browser, hybrid apps are installed locally but use the cloud","Hybrid apps are only used by enterprises"],2,"Web-based applications operate entirely through a browser and do not require local installation, while hybrid cloud applications (like Microsoft 365) are installed on the local system but depend on cloud connectivity for features such as real-time collaboration, auto- saving, and syncing.","Virtualization and Cloud Computing"],["Scenario: You are helping a team member install an enterprise cloud app that requires company-wide login credentials. After installation, the app fails to launch. Which of the following should you check first?",["The user’s internet speed","Whether the user has SSO configured and VPN connected","If the app has been bookmarked","If two-factor authentication is turned off"],1,"Enterprise applications often require Single Sign-On (SSO) and secure network access (like a corporate VPN) as part of their authentication and policy enforcement. Failing to meet these requirements can prevent the application from launching properly or verifying the user's credentials.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["What should a user do if a web-based cloud application is not loading in their browser?",["Restart the computer and reinstall the app","Contact the cloud provider’s legal department","Clear the browser cache and disable extensions","Wait 24 hours before retrying"],2,"A common cause of loading issues in web-based applications is a cluttered or outdated browser cache and interfering browser extensions. Clearing the cache and disabling unnecessary extensions helps ensure compatibility and smooth performance.","Software Troubleshooting"],["A user in a small office reports seeing unknown devices connected to the network. Which SOHO security feature could help prevent this issue in the future?",["File encryption","MAC address filtering","VPN configuration","Disabling browser pop-ups"],1,"MAC address filtering limits network access to known and approved devices. This is a common SOHO-level control to help reduce unauthorized wireless connections to a local network.","Networking"],["Which network security control would be most effective in recovering from a ransomware attack that spread across your entire network?",["Role-based access control","Strong password enforcement","Regular backups","Network segmentation"],2,"While all options are important, regular and reliable backups ensure that data can be recovered without paying a ransom if ransomware encrypts critical files. Backups are one of the most effective protections against data loss from malware.","Networking"],["Scenario: An organization experiences a phishing attack that led to unauthorized access. What are two immediate actions that should be taken according to incident response best practices?",["Conduct a full system restore from backup","Notify law enforcement immediately","Isolate affected systems","Follow the incident response plan (IRP)"],2,"In any security incident, containing the threat is critical—isolating affected systems prevents further compromise. Following the predefined IRP ensures that all response actions are structured, compliant, and minimize damage.","Security"],["Which of the following is the most effective way to prevent unauthorized access to a SOHO router?",["Disabling the firewall","Keeping the default username and password","Enabling WPA3 encryption and changing the default admin credentials","Allowing remote administration for easy troubleshooting"],2,"Default admin credentials are widely known or easily guessed, making them a common attack target on SOHO routers. Enabling WPA3 encryption secures the wireless connection itself, while changing the default admin username and password closes off the management interface from casual attackers.","Security"],["A small business owner wants to access their office network remotely and is considering using port forwarding to allow RDP (Remote Desktop Protocol) access. Which of the following best describes the risks of this approach and a more secure alternative?",["Port forwarding improves performance but should only be used with dynamic IP addresses; using RDP over 443 is a secure workaround.","Port forwarding is safe if antivirus software is installed; adding a firewall exception will prevent attacks.","Port forwarding increases the risk of unauthorized access and attacks; using a VPN is a more secure and encrypted method for remote access.","RDP should only be used during business hours; limiting login attempts is enough to prevent all types of attacks."],2,"Port forwarding opens a specific port on the router directly to the internet, which attackers can scan for and exploit even if the target service requires a login. A VPN instead creates an encrypted tunnel into the network, so RDP traffic never has to be exposed directly to the public internet.","Networking"],["What is the primary purpose of a phishing attack?",["To gain unauthorized physical access to a building","To trick individuals into revealing confidential information","To install hardware keyloggers on a victim’s device","To exploit software vulnerabilities in operating systems"],1,"A phishing attack is a type of social engineering tactic used to deceive individuals into giving away sensitive information, such as passwords, credit card numbers, or login credentials. Attackers often use emails or fake websites that appear legitimate to create a sense of urgency or trust.","Security"],["Scenario: You are leaving your office building when someone in a delivery uniform asks you to hold the door open for them. They claim to have an urgent package for a colleague but do not have an access badge. What is the best course of action?",["Hold the door open since they appear legitimate","Ask them to wait and notify security or the intended recipient","Allow them in, but escort them to the recipient’s office","Ignore them and continue walking"],1,"This situation is an example of tailgating, a physical security risk where someone attempts to gain unauthorized access by following someone with legitimate access. Even if the person seems trustworthy, the correct response is to follow protocol: notify security personnel or the recipient directly.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["What is the best method to prevent sensitive information from being stolen through dumpster diving?",["Storing old documents in a locked cabinet","Shredding all sensitive documents before disposal","Using complex passwords for all accounts","Avoiding public Wi-Fi connections"],1,"Dumpster diving involves searching through trash or recycling to find discarded items containing confidential information, such as account numbers, passwords, or internal documents. The most effective way to prevent this kind of data theft is to shred sensitive documents before they are thrown away.","Security"],["Which of the following is the best reason for enabling automatic browser updates?",["To improve internet speed","To ensure the latest security patches are applied","To prevent websites from tracking your activity","To install new browser extensions automatically"],1,"Enabling automatic browser updates ensures that the browser receives the most recent security patches and bug fixes as soon as they are available. This helps protect against newly discovered vulnerabilities that could be exploited by attackers.","Security"],["Scenario: A company employee installs a new browser extension to improve productivity. Afterward, they notice unexpected pop-ups and unauthorized access to their accounts. What is the most likely cause of this issue?",["The browser cache was not cleared before installing the extension","The extension was downloaded from an untrusted source","The company network was compromised before the installation","The employee failed to disable JavaScript before installing the extension"],1,"Installing extensions from untrusted sources can lead to malicious software being added to the browser. These extensions may include spyware, adware, or credential stealers that can generate pop-ups and access sensitive data without the user's knowledge.","Security"],["What is an example of a common software vulnerability that attackers exploit?",["Strong passwords","Multi-factor authentication","Buffer overflow","Firewall rules"],2,"A buffer overflow occurs when a program writes more data to a memory buffer than it was allocated to hold, corrupting adjacent memory. Attackers can exploit this to crash a program or, in more severe cases, execute arbitrary code, making it one of the most common and dangerous software vulnerabilities.","Security"],["Which of the following best describes a zero-day exploit?",["An attack targeting a known vulnerability with an available patch","An attack that exploits a vulnerability before a patch is released","A phishing attack using fake emails to steal information","A brute-force attack attempting to guess passwords"],1,"A zero-day exploit targets a vulnerability that the software vendor doesn't yet know about or hasn't had time to patch. Because no fix exists yet, zero-day attacks are especially dangerous and difficult to defend against until a patch is released.","Security"],["Which real-world security incident was caused by an unpatched software vulnerability?",["Twitter Insider Attack (2020)","Equifax Data Breach (2017)","Colonial Pipeline Ransomware Attack (2021)","Sony PlayStation Network Hack (2011)"],1,"The 2017 Equifax data breach exposed the personal data of roughly 147 million people after attackers exploited a known, unpatched vulnerability in the Apache Struts web framework. Equifax had a patch available for months before the breach, making it a textbook example of the risk of delayed patch management.","Security"],["What is the main purpose of an Intrusion Detection System (IDS)?",["Encrypt network traffic","Detect and alert administrators of suspicious activity","Prevent unauthorized users from logging in","Scan for viruses on a system"],1,"An Intrusion Detection System (IDS) passively monitors network or system traffic for suspicious activity and alerts administrators when it finds something, but it does not block traffic itself. That active-blocking role belongs to an Intrusion Prevention System (IPS), which sits inline and can stop traffic in real time.","Security"],["A user reports that their laptop keyboard is no longer responding. What is the most likely solution?",["Replace individual keys that are not working","Replace the entire keyboard assembly","Update the laptop’s firmware","Use a compressed air canister to clean under the keys"],1,"Laptop keyboards are typically built as a single integrated unit, making it difficult or impossible to replace individual keys. If multiple keys fail or the entire keyboard stops responding, the most effective fix is to replace the full keyboard assembly.","Mobile Devices"],["Scenario: A graphic designer is looking for a device that allows precise digital drawing while maintaining portability. What accessory should they consider?",["USB-C docking station","Trackpoint","Drawing pad","Bluetooth keyboard"],2,"A drawing pad (also known as a graphics tablet) is designed to offer precision input with a stylus, making it ideal for digital art and design. These devices are often lightweight and portable, allowing users to create detailed work while on the move.","Mobile Devices"],["A technician is working on a tablet that frequently shuts down while in use. The device is also warm to the touch. What is the most likely issue?",["Malware infection","Swollen battery","Overheating","Poor Wi-Fi signal"],2,"Frequent shutdowns and the device feeling hot are strong indicators of overheating. Tablets can shut down automatically to prevent heat damage to internal components. Blocked vents, background processes, or intensive app usage may contribute to rising temperatures.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["Which operating system tool can be used to adjust sleep and brightness settings on a laptop?",["Device Manager","Disk Management","Power Options","Task Manager"],2,"The Power Options tool in Windows allows users to customize sleep settings, screen brightness, and battery performance modes. It’s essential for managing how a laptop uses energy and enters low-power states. This helps improve both battery life and user convenience.","Mobile Devices"],["A smartphone battery swells and the case begins to separate. What should a technician do first?",["Continue using the device until it stops charging","Place the phone in a sealed bag and freeze it","Stop using the device immediately and seek replacement","Update the mobile operating system"],2,"A swollen battery is a serious safety hazard that can lead to leakage, fire, or explosion. The device should be powered off immediately and no longer used or charged. It must be handled carefully and replaced by a qualified technician using a manufacturer- approved part.","Mobile Devices"],["Scenario: A technician needs to lift a heavy PC tower off the floor. What is the correct lifting technique to avoid injury?",["Bend at the waist and lift with your back","Lift with your legs, keeping your back straight","Twist your body while lifting to save time","Lift quickly to minimize strain"],1,"Proper lifting technique involves bending at the knees and lifting with your legs while keeping your back straight, which distributes the load to stronger leg muscles and reduces the risk of back injury. Bending at the waist or twisting while lifting are common causes of workplace back injuries.","Operational Procedures"],["Scenario: You need to dispose of an old lead-acid UPS battery. What is the proper disposal method?",["Throw it in regular trash","Recycle it through a certified battery recycling program","Bury it in the backyard","Burn it"],1,"Lead-acid batteries contain hazardous materials and must be recycled through a certified program in accordance with environmental regulations, not thrown in regular trash. Most retailers that sell batteries also accept them for recycling.","Operational Procedures"],["Before working on any component that requires an MSDS/SDS reference, what should a technician do?",["Skip it, an SDS is optional","Locate and review the Safety Data Sheet for proper handling and disposal","Call the fire department","Ignore chemical warning labels"],1,"A Safety Data Sheet (SDS, formerly MSDS) provides detailed information on the safe handling, storage, and disposal of hazardous materials. Technicians should consult it before working with unfamiliar chemicals or components like toner or batteries.","Operational Procedures"],["Scenario: A customer is frustrated and raising their voice about a repeated issue. What is the best way to de-escalate the situation?",["Argue back to defend yourself","Actively listen, avoid interrupting, and acknowledge their frustration","Transfer them immediately without comment","Ignore their tone and talk over them"],1,"Professional communication best practices call for active listening and acknowledging the customer's frustration without being defensive or dismissive. This helps de-escalate the situation and rebuild trust before working toward a resolution.","Operational Procedures"],["What is the purpose of a change management process when making updates to a production server?",["To slow down IT work unnecessarily","To document, review, and approve changes before they're implemented, reducing the risk of unplanned outages","To avoid ever making changes","To bypass documentation requirements"],1,"Change management ensures changes are properly documented, reviewed for risk, and approved before implementation. This process includes a rollback plan and helps prevent unplanned downtime caused by untested or uncoordinated changes.","Operational Procedures"],["A user's computer may contain material that is evidence in a workplace investigation. What is the correct first step?",["Continue using the computer normally","Preserve chain of custody by documenting and securing the device before any further action","Delete any suspicious files","Reformat the drive"],1,"When a device may contain evidence, maintaining chain of custody is critical: document who has handled the device and when, and secure it to prevent tampering. Continuing to use, altering, or wiping the device could destroy evidence and compromise any investigation.","Operational Procedures"],["Which of the following is an example of PII that must be handled according to data privacy regulations?",["A company's public marketing brochure","A customer's Social Security number","The office Wi-Fi SSID","A printer's IP address"],1,"Personally Identifiable Information (PII) includes data such as a Social Security number that can be used to identify a specific individual. Organizations must handle PII according to applicable privacy regulations and company policy, including secure storage and limited access.","Operational Procedures"],["Scenario: A technician wants to work on a production server during business hours because it's more convenient. What should they consider first?",["Business hours are always fine for any change","Whether a maintenance window has been scheduled to minimize impact on users","Nothing, they should just proceed","Only their own personal schedule"],1,"Changes to production systems should generally be scheduled during an approved maintenance window, often outside business hours, to minimize disruption to users. This is a core part of standard change management procedure.","Operational Procedures"],["What is the main difference between a Type 1 and a Type 2 hypervisor?",["Type 1 runs directly on hardware; Type 2 runs on top of a host operating system","Type 1 is always free; Type 2 always costs money","Type 1 only supports Linux; Type 2 only supports Windows","There is no real difference"],0,"A Type 1 (bare-metal) hypervisor runs directly on physical hardware, offering better performance and is common in data centers (e.g., VMware ESXi, Hyper-V server). A Type 2 (hosted) hypervisor runs as an application on top of an existing operating system (e.g., VirtualBox, VMware Workstation), which is more common for desktop use.","Virtualization and Cloud Computing"],["Why might an IT administrator take a snapshot of a virtual machine before applying a major update?",["To increase the VM's CPU allocation","To create a restore point they can revert to if the update causes problems","To permanently delete the VM","To share the VM with other departments"],1,"A snapshot captures the state of a VM at a specific point in time. If an update or configuration change causes problems, the administrator can quickly revert to the snapshot rather than rebuilding the VM from scratch.","Virtualization and Cloud Computing"],["What is a key resource requirement to consider before creating a new virtual machine on a host?",["The physical location of the host server only","Whether the host has enough available CPU, RAM, and storage to support the new VM","The color of the server case","The brand of the network cable"],1,"Before provisioning a VM, an administrator must confirm the host has sufficient CPU cores, RAM, and storage capacity available, since overcommitting these resources can degrade performance for all VMs running on that host.","Virtualization and Cloud Computing"],["A company wants to use cloud resources for a short-term project without any long-term commitment. Which billing model best supports this?",["A five-year reserved contract","Pay-as-you-go / consumption-based billing","A one-time perpetual license","A fixed annual subscription regardless of usage"],1,"Pay-as-you-go (consumption-based) billing lets organizations pay only for the cloud resources they actually use, with no long-term commitment. This is ideal for short-term or unpredictable workloads, unlike reserved or fixed-term contracts.","Virtualization and Cloud Computing"],["What is the purpose of file synchronization services like OneDrive or Google Drive in a cloud context?",["To physically back up files onto USB drives only","To keep files automatically updated and accessible across multiple devices via the cloud","To delete old files automatically","To intentionally slow down internet speeds"],1,"Cloud file synchronization services keep a copy of files in the cloud and automatically sync changes across all devices linked to the account, ensuring the most current version is available anywhere with an internet connection.","Virtualization and Cloud Computing"],["Which cloud characteristic allows a service to automatically scale resources up or down based on current demand?",["Rapid elasticity","Metered service","Broad network access","Resource isolation"],0,"Rapid elasticity is a core cloud computing characteristic that allows resources to be automatically scaled up during high demand and scaled back down when demand decreases, so organizations only use (and pay for) what they need.","Virtualization and Cloud Computing"],["Scenario: A company wants full control over its infrastructure security but also wants to reduce hardware costs for a new customer-facing web application. Which cloud deployment model is the best fit?",["Public cloud only","Private cloud only","Hybrid cloud, keeping sensitive backend data private while hosting the public-facing app in the public cloud","No cloud, on-premises only"],2,"A hybrid cloud model allows an organization to keep sensitive or highly regulated workloads on a private cloud (or on-premises) while taking advantage of the public cloud's scalability and lower cost for public-facing applications, combining the benefits of both.","Virtualization and Cloud Computing"],["A technician needs to reset a smartphone to factory settings before it is resold. What should they do first?",["Immediately perform the factory reset","Back up important data and remove any accounts, like an Apple ID or Google account, tied to the device, then factory reset","Physically destroy the device","Sell it without resetting anything"],1,"Before performing a factory reset, back up any data the user wants to keep, and remove accounts like an Apple ID or Google account. Failing to remove these accounts can leave activation locks in place, such as Find My iPhone Activation Lock, making the device unusable for the next owner.","Mobile Devices"],["A user's smartphone screen has become unresponsive to touch in one corner, but the rest of the screen works fine. What is the most likely cause?",["A software update is needed","Digitizer damage, often from a crack or drop","Weak Wi-Fi signal","Low battery"],1,"The digitizer is the touch-sensitive layer on top of the display. Localized touch issues, especially after a drop or with a visible crack, often indicate physical digitizer damage rather than a software problem.","Mobile Devices"],["Which mobile device connectivity method uses short-range communication for tasks like contactless payments?",["Bluetooth","NFC (Near Field Communication)","Cellular data","GPS"],1,"NFC enables very short-range, a few centimeters, wireless communication and is commonly used for tasks like mobile payments (Apple Pay, Google Pay) and quick device pairing, unlike Bluetooth which has a longer range for ongoing connections.","Mobile Devices"],["A company wants employees to use their personal phones for work email but needs the ability to remotely wipe corporate data if the phone is lost. Which technology enables this?",["MDM (Mobile Device Management)","A stronger Wi-Fi password","A larger phone screen","A faster cellular plan"],0,"Mobile Device Management (MDM) software allows organizations to enforce security policies, remotely lock or wipe devices, and manage corporate data on both company-owned and BYOD (Bring Your Own Device) devices.","Mobile Devices"],["A user's tablet battery drains extremely fast even when not in use. What troubleshooting step should be tried first?",["Replace the entire tablet","Check for apps running in the background and review battery usage statistics in settings","Reinstall the operating system immediately","Ignore it, this is normal"],1,"Checking battery usage statistics in the device settings can quickly reveal which apps are consuming excessive power in the background. This is a fast, non-destructive first troubleshooting step before considering more drastic measures.","Mobile Devices"],["What is the primary purpose of pairing a Bluetooth headset with a smartphone?",["To charge the phone wirelessly","To establish a short-range wireless connection for audio without cables","To connect to the cellular network","To increase phone storage"],1,"Bluetooth pairing creates a short-range wireless link between two devices, commonly used to connect headsets, speakers, keyboards, and other peripherals to a smartphone without physical cables.","Mobile Devices"],["A field technician needs a mobile device with GPS, cellular data, and the ability to run inventory management software independently, with no reliance on a paired phone. What type of device best fits this need?",["A basic Bluetooth tracker","A rugged tablet with built-in cellular connectivity","A smartwatch","A wireless keyboard"],1,"A rugged tablet with built-in cellular, not just Wi-Fi, connectivity provides the independent computing power, GPS, and durability needed for field work like inventory management, without depending on a paired smartphone for connectivity.","Mobile Devices"],["A user reports their computer is running extremely slow, and Task Manager shows one unfamiliar process consuming 99% of the CPU. What should the technician suspect first?",["The monitor is failing","Possible malware or a runaway, misbehaving process","The keyboard needs replacing","The Wi-Fi router is broken"],1,"An unfamiliar process consuming nearly all CPU resources is a common symptom of malware or a malfunctioning application. The technician should investigate the process, check it against known malware signatures, and consider running a full antivirus/anti-malware scan.","Software Troubleshooting"],["After a Windows update, a user's computer boots to a black screen with only a cursor visible. What is a reasonable first troubleshooting step?",["Immediately reinstall Windows from scratch","Boot into Safe Mode and roll back the recent update or driver","Replace the motherboard","Physically shake the computer"],1,"Booting into Safe Mode allows a technician to load a minimal set of drivers and troubleshoot the issue, such as rolling back a problematic update or driver, without needing to immediately resort to a full reinstall.","Software Troubleshooting"],["A user's application repeatedly crashes with the same error message. What is a good next troubleshooting step after simply restarting the application?",["Immediately replace the hard drive","Check for and install available application and OS updates, or reinstall the application","Unplug the monitor","Change the desktop wallpaper"],1,"Outdated or corrupted application files are a common cause of repeated crashes. Checking for updates or performing a clean reinstall of the application often resolves the issue by replacing corrupted files with fresh ones.","Software Troubleshooting"],["What is the purpose of booting into Safe Mode when troubleshooting a Windows issue?",["It permanently deletes all installed programs","It starts Windows with only essential drivers and services, helping isolate problems caused by third-party software or drivers","It increases the computer's processing speed","It disables the keyboard and mouse"],1,"Safe Mode loads Windows with a minimal set of drivers and services, disabling most third-party software and startup programs. This helps technicians determine whether an issue is caused by a driver, startup program, or the core OS itself.","Software Troubleshooting"],["A user's browser is redirecting all searches to an unfamiliar website and showing excessive pop-up ads. What is the most likely cause?",["The user's internet plan expired","A browser hijacker or adware infection","The monitor's resolution is set too low","The keyboard language is incorrect"],1,"Unwanted search redirects and excessive pop-ups are classic symptoms of a browser hijacker or adware, often installed unintentionally alongside free software. Removal typically involves running anti-malware scans and resetting browser settings and extensions.","Software Troubleshooting"],["Which Windows tool would a technician use to see which programs launch automatically at startup, in order to speed up boot time?",["Disk Cleanup","Task Manager's Startup tab","Notepad","Control Panel's Fonts settings"],1,"The Startup tab in Task Manager lists all programs configured to launch when Windows starts, along with their impact on startup time, allowing a technician to disable unnecessary ones to improve boot performance.","Software Troubleshooting"],["A user reports that a previously working application now shows a \"missing DLL\" error. What is a likely cause and fix?",["The application's monitor cable is loose; reconnect it","A required shared library file was deleted or corrupted; reinstalling the application often restores it","The user's password expired; reset it","The printer is out of paper"],1,"A \"missing DLL\" error means the application can't find a shared library file it depends on, often due to accidental deletion, a corrupted file, or a conflicting uninstall from another program. Reinstalling the application typically restores the missing files.","Software Troubleshooting"],["A desktop computer powers on, fans spin, but there is no display output and no POST beep. What should a technician check first?",["Reinstall the operating system","Reseat the RAM and check that the video cable is connected to the correct port, dedicated GPU vs. onboard","Replace the hard drive","Update the web browser"],1,"No display with no POST beep is often caused by improperly seated RAM or a video cable plugged into the wrong output, such as the motherboard's onboard port when a dedicated GPU is installed. These are simple, non-destructive checks to perform before assuming a bigger hardware failure.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["A user reports their computer randomly reboots when running graphics-intensive applications. What are the two most likely causes to investigate first?",["Overheating and an insufficient or failing power supply","Wrong wallpaper and outdated browser","Slow internet and low disk space","Wrong keyboard layout and mouse sensitivity"],0,"Random reboots under heavy load are classic symptoms of overheating, inadequate cooling for the CPU/GPU, or an underpowered/failing power supply that can't sustain the increased power draw of demanding applications.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["A network printer that was working yesterday is now showing \"offline\" for all users. What is a reasonable first troubleshooting step?",["Replace the printer immediately","Verify the printer has power and a valid network connection, and check if its IP address has changed","Reinstall the operating system on every computer","Buy a new router"],1,"A shared network printer showing offline for everyone usually points to a connectivity issue, such as the printer losing power or network connection, or having its IP address change, for example from a DHCP lease renewal, so it no longer matches what's configured on client computers.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["A user's external hard drive makes a repeated clicking noise and is not recognized by the computer. What does this most likely indicate?",["A software driver needs updating","Mechanical failure of the hard drive","The USB cable is the wrong color","The file system needs to be changed to exFAT"],1,"A repeated clicking noise from a hard drive, often called the \"click of death,\" is a classic sign of mechanical failure, such as the read/write head failing to find data correctly. The priority at this point should shift to backing up any recoverable data rather than continuing normal use.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["Which tool would a technician use to test whether a specific network cable run is wired correctly end-to-end?",["A cable tester or certifier","A screwdriver","A multimeter set to measure temperature","A can of compressed air"],0,"A cable tester, or certifier for more advanced testing, checks that each wire in a cable run is properly connected pin-to-pin at both ends, identifying issues like shorts, opens, or miswires such as reversed pairs.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["A laptop won't charge even though it's plugged in, but it does turn on and run from battery. What should be checked first?",["The laptop's operating system version","The charging cable, AC adapter, and charging port for damage or debris","The installed antivirus software","The desktop wallpaper settings"],1,"If a laptop runs on battery but won't charge while plugged in, the most likely causes are a damaged charging cable or AC adapter, or a charging port with debris or damage preventing a solid connection. These physical components should be checked before assuming a more complex internal fault.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["Identify the cable/connector shown in the image.",["USB-A","RJ-45 (Ethernet)","SATA (Data)","Micro-USB"],1,"This is RJ-45 (Ethernet): 8P8C modular plug. Speed: Up to 10 Gbps (Cat6a) / 1 Gbps (Cat5e, Cat6). Max distance: 100 m (328 ft) per segment. Used for: Wired networking: connecting PCs, switches, routers, and access points over twisted-pair cable.","Hardware","<svg viewBox=\"0 0 160 110\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n    <rect x=\"50\" y=\"35\" width=\"60\" height=\"45\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#3b82f6\"/>\n    <rect x=\"68\" y=\"18\" width=\"24\" height=\"20\" fill=\"#2563eb\"/>\n    <rect x=\"58.0\" y=\"40\" width=\"3.5\" height=\"26\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"63.5\" y=\"40\" width=\"3.5\" height=\"26\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"69.0\" y=\"40\" width=\"3.5\" height=\"26\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"74.5\" y=\"40\" width=\"3.5\" height=\"26\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"80.0\" y=\"40\" width=\"3.5\" height=\"26\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"85.5\" y=\"40\" width=\"3.5\" height=\"26\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"91.0\" y=\"40\" width=\"3.5\" height=\"26\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"96.5\" y=\"40\" width=\"3.5\" height=\"26\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/>\n  </svg>"],["Identify the cable/connector shown in the image.",["Fiber Optic (SC/LC/ST)","RJ-11 (Phone/DSL)","DisplayPort","USB-A"],1,"This is RJ-11 (Phone/DSL): 6P4C or 6P2C modular plug. Speed: Varies (DSL up to ~100 Mbps depending on distance/standard). Max distance: Several km for telephone lines (with signal degradation). Used for: Landline telephone connections and DSL internet modems. Smaller and narrower than RJ-45.","Hardware","<svg viewBox=\"0 0 160 110\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n    <rect x=\"58\" y=\"35\" width=\"44\" height=\"45\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#3b82f6\"/>\n    <rect x=\"71.2\" y=\"18\" width=\"17.6\" height=\"20\" fill=\"#2563eb\"/>\n    <rect x=\"66.0\" y=\"40\" width=\"5.0\" height=\"26\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"73.0\" y=\"40\" width=\"5.0\" height=\"26\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"80.0\" y=\"40\" width=\"5.0\" height=\"26\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"87.0\" y=\"40\" width=\"5.0\" height=\"26\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/>\n  </svg>"],["Identify the cable/connector shown in the image.",["Molex","Fiber Optic (SC/LC/ST)","Coaxial (RG-6)","DisplayPort"],2,"This is Coaxial (RG-6): F-connector (threaded). Speed: Up to 1 Gbps+ (DOCSIS 3.1 cable internet). Max distance: Up to ~150 ft (45 m) for cable internet runs before signal loss becomes an issue. Used for: Cable internet/TV connections; connects a cable modem to a wall outlet.","Hardware","<svg viewBox=\"0 0 160 110\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n    <circle cx=\"80\" cy=\"55\" r=\"30\" fill=\"#3b82f6\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"80\" cy=\"55\" r=\"22\" fill=\"#1e293b\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"80\" cy=\"55\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/>\n    <rect x=\"45\" y=\"49\" width=\"14\" height=\"12\" fill=\"#3b82f6\"/>\n    <rect x=\"101\" y=\"49\" width=\"14\" height=\"12\" fill=\"#3b82f6\"/>\n  </svg>"],["Identify the cable/connector shown in the image.",["Molex","RJ-45 (Ethernet)","Fiber Optic (SC/LC/ST)","Lightning"],2,"This is Fiber Optic (SC/LC/ST): SC (snap-in), LC (small form-factor duplex), or ST (bayonet twist-lock). Speed: 10 Gbps to 100+ Gbps depending on standard. Max distance: Hundreds of meters (multi-mode) to 40+ km (single-mode). Used for: High-speed, long-distance networking and backbone links; immune to electromagnetic interference.","Hardware","<svg viewBox=\"0 0 160 110\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n    <rect x=\"45\" y=\"30\" width=\"70\" height=\"50\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"#3b82f6\"/>\n    <rect x=\"55\" y=\"40\" width=\"20\" height=\"30\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#0f1729\"/>\n    <rect x=\"85\" y=\"40\" width=\"20\" height=\"30\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#0f1729\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"65\" cy=\"55\" r=\"4\" fill=\"#4ade80\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"95\" cy=\"55\" r=\"4\" fill=\"#4ade80\"/>\n  </svg>"],["Identify the cable/connector shown in the image.",["SATA (Power)","Coaxial (RG-6)","USB-A","HDMI"],2,"This is USB-A: Rectangular, 4 or 9 pins. Speed: Up to 5 Gbps (USB 3.x) / 480 Mbps (USB 2.0). Max distance: Typically under 5 m without an active extender. Used for: The classic flat USB connector for keyboards, mice, flash drives, and older peripherals.","Hardware","<svg viewBox=\"0 0 160 110\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n    <rect x=\"35\" y=\"35\" width=\"90\" height=\"40\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#3b82f6\"/>\n    <rect x=\"45\" y=\"43\" width=\"70\" height=\"8\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/>\n    <rect x=\"45\" y=\"59\" width=\"70\" height=\"8\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/>\n  </svg>"],["Identify the cable/connector shown in the image.",["Molex","RJ-11 (Phone/DSL)","SATA (Data)","USB-C"],3,"This is USB-C: Oval, reversible, 24 pins. Speed: Up to 20 Gbps (USB 3.2) or 40 Gbps (Thunderbolt 3/4 over USB-C). Max distance: Typically under 2-3 m for full-speed data. Used for: Modern reversible connector for phones, laptops, and peripherals; also carries video (DisplayPort Alt Mode) and up to 100-240W of power delivery.","Hardware","<svg viewBox=\"0 0 160 110\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n    <rect x=\"40\" y=\"38\" width=\"80\" height=\"34\" rx=\"17\" fill=\"#3b82f6\"/>\n    <rect x=\"52\" y=\"48\" width=\"56\" height=\"14\" rx=\"7\" fill=\"#0f1729\"/>\n  </svg>"],["Identify the cable/connector shown in the image.",["DVI","USB-C","Micro-USB","VGA"],2,"This is Micro-USB: Small trapezoidal plug, 5 pins. Speed: Up to 480 Mbps (USB 2.0) typically. Max distance: Typically under 2 m. Used for: Common on older Android phones, external hard drives, and other small peripherals before USB-C became standard.","Hardware","<svg viewBox=\"0 0 160 110\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n    <path d=\"M55 35 L105 35 L110 75 L50 75 Z\" fill=\"#3b82f6\"/>\n    <rect x=\"65\" y=\"45\" width=\"30\" height=\"6\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/>\n  </svg>"],["Identify the cable/connector shown in the image.",["USB-A","Coaxial (RG-6)","Lightning","VGA"],2,"This is Lightning: Apple proprietary, 8-pin, reversible. Speed: Comparable to USB 2.0 speeds on most devices. Max distance: Typically under 2 m. Used for: Apple's proprietary connector for iPhone, iPad, and accessories (being phased out in favor of USB-C on newer devices).","Hardware","<svg viewBox=\"0 0 160 110\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n    <rect x=\"60\" y=\"25\" width=\"40\" height=\"60\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#3b82f6\"/>\n    <rect x=\"68\" y=\"35\" width=\"24\" height=\"6\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/>\n    <rect x=\"68\" y=\"47\" width=\"24\" height=\"6\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/>\n    <rect x=\"68\" y=\"59\" width=\"24\" height=\"6\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/>\n    <rect x=\"68\" y=\"71\" width=\"24\" height=\"6\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/>\n  </svg>"],["Identify the cable/connector shown in the image.",["SATA (Data)","RJ-45 (Ethernet)","HDMI","Micro-USB"],2,"This is HDMI: 19-pin, trapezoidal. Speed: Up to 48 Gbps (HDMI 2.1). Max distance: Typically under 15 ft (5 m) without an active/amplified cable. Used for: Carries digital video and audio together; the most common connector for monitors, TVs, and projectors.","Hardware","<svg viewBox=\"0 0 160 110\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n    <path d=\"M35 40 L110 40 L125 55 L110 70 L35 70 Z\" fill=\"#3b82f6\"/>\n    <rect x=\"43.0\" y=\"48\" width=\"4\" height=\"14\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"49.5\" y=\"48\" width=\"4\" height=\"14\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"56.0\" y=\"48\" width=\"4\" height=\"14\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"62.5\" y=\"48\" width=\"4\" height=\"14\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"69.0\" y=\"48\" width=\"4\" height=\"14\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"75.5\" y=\"48\" width=\"4\" height=\"14\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"82.0\" y=\"48\" width=\"4\" height=\"14\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"88.5\" y=\"48\" width=\"4\" height=\"14\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"95.0\" y=\"48\" width=\"4\" height=\"14\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"101.5\" y=\"48\" width=\"4\" height=\"14\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"108.0\" y=\"48\" width=\"4\" height=\"14\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"114.5\" y=\"48\" width=\"4\" height=\"14\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/>\n  </svg>"],["Identify the cable/connector shown in the image.",["DisplayPort","Coaxial (RG-6)","Molex","RJ-11 (Phone/DSL)"],0,"This is DisplayPort: 20-pin with one beveled corner. Speed: Up to 80 Gbps (DisplayPort 2.1). Max distance: Typically under 15 ft (5 m) passively. Used for: Digital video/audio connector common on PCs and monitors; supports daisy-chaining multiple monitors (MST).","Hardware","<svg viewBox=\"0 0 160 110\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n    <path d=\"M35 35 L110 35 L110 70 L45 70 L35 60 Z\" fill=\"#3b82f6\"/>\n    <rect x=\"42.0\" y=\"45\" width=\"4\" height=\"16\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"48.8\" y=\"45\" width=\"4\" height=\"16\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"55.6\" y=\"45\" width=\"4\" height=\"16\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"62.4\" y=\"45\" width=\"4\" height=\"16\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"69.2\" y=\"45\" width=\"4\" height=\"16\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"76.0\" y=\"45\" width=\"4\" height=\"16\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"82.8\" y=\"45\" width=\"4\" height=\"16\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"89.6\" y=\"45\" width=\"4\" height=\"16\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"96.4\" y=\"45\" width=\"4\" height=\"16\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><rect x=\"103.2\" y=\"45\" width=\"4\" height=\"16\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/>\n  </svg>"],["Identify the cable/connector shown in the image.",["HDMI","VGA","RJ-11 (Phone/DSL)","Fiber Optic (SC/LC/ST)"],1,"This is VGA: DE-15, 15 pins in 3 rows, usually blue. Speed: Analog signal - not rated in bps. Max distance: Up to ~50 ft (15 m) before noticeable quality loss. Used for: Legacy analog video connector, largely replaced by HDMI/DisplayPort but still found on older monitors and projectors.","Hardware","<svg viewBox=\"0 0 160 110\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n    <path d=\"M40 30 L120 30 L112 82 L48 82 Z\" fill=\"#2563eb\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"52.0\" cy=\"43.0\" r=\"3\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"66.0\" cy=\"43.0\" r=\"3\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"80.0\" cy=\"43.0\" r=\"3\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"94.0\" cy=\"43.0\" r=\"3\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"108.0\" cy=\"43.0\" r=\"3\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"52.0\" cy=\"55.0\" r=\"3\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"66.0\" cy=\"55.0\" r=\"3\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"80.0\" cy=\"55.0\" r=\"3\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"94.0\" cy=\"55.0\" r=\"3\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"108.0\" cy=\"55.0\" r=\"3\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"52.0\" cy=\"67.0\" r=\"3\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"66.0\" cy=\"67.0\" r=\"3\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"80.0\" cy=\"67.0\" r=\"3\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"94.0\" cy=\"67.0\" r=\"3\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"108.0\" cy=\"67.0\" r=\"3\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/>\n  </svg>"],["Identify the cable/connector shown in the image.",["DVI","DisplayPort","USB-A","RJ-45 (Ethernet)"],0,"This is DVI: Up to 24+1 pins, white connector. Speed: Digital: up to ~9.9 Gbps (Dual-Link DVI-D). Max distance: Typically under 15 ft (5 m). Used for: Digital (and sometimes analog) video connector bridging the gap between VGA and HDMI; no audio support.","Hardware","<svg viewBox=\"0 0 160 110\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n    <rect x=\"32\" y=\"28\" width=\"96\" height=\"48\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#f1f5f9\"/>\n    <rect x=\"105\" y=\"42\" width=\"16\" height=\"20\" fill=\"#cbd5e1\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"42.0\" cy=\"38.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"52.0\" cy=\"38.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"62.0\" cy=\"38.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"72.0\" cy=\"38.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"82.0\" cy=\"38.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"92.0\" cy=\"38.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"42.0\" cy=\"46.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"52.0\" cy=\"46.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"62.0\" cy=\"46.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"72.0\" cy=\"46.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"82.0\" cy=\"46.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"92.0\" cy=\"46.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"42.0\" cy=\"54.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"52.0\" cy=\"54.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"62.0\" cy=\"54.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"72.0\" cy=\"54.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"82.0\" cy=\"54.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"92.0\" cy=\"54.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"42.0\" cy=\"62.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"52.0\" cy=\"62.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"62.0\" cy=\"62.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"72.0\" cy=\"62.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"82.0\" cy=\"62.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/><circle cx=\"92.0\" cy=\"62.0\" r=\"2.3\" fill=\"#334155\"/>\n  </svg>"],["Identify the cable/connector shown in the image.",["SATA (Data)","RJ-11 (Phone/DSL)","Fiber Optic (SC/LC/ST)","DisplayPort"],0,"This is SATA (Data): 7-pin, L-shaped keyed connector. Speed: Up to 6 Gbps (SATA III). Max distance: Up to 1 m (39 in) per the SATA spec. Used for: Connects internal hard drives and SSDs to the motherboard for data transfer.","Hardware","<svg viewBox=\"0 0 160 110\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n    <path d=\"M35 40 L100 40 L112 50 L100 60 L35 60 Z\" fill=\"#3b82f6\"/>\n    <rect x=\"40\" y=\"45\" width=\"55\" height=\"10\" fill=\"#0f1729\"/>\n  </svg>"],["Identify the cable/connector shown in the image.",["SATA (Data)","RJ-45 (Ethernet)","Lightning","SATA (Power)"],3,"This is SATA (Power): 15-pin, flat L-shaped keyed connector. Speed: N/A (power only). Max distance: Limited by internal case routing. Used for: Supplies power from the PSU to SATA hard drives, SSDs, and optical drives.","Hardware","<svg viewBox=\"0 0 160 110\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n    <path d=\"M30 38 L118 38 L108 72 L40 72 Z\" fill=\"#f97316\"/>\n    <rect x=\"40\" y=\"47\" width=\"68\" height=\"12\" fill=\"#1e293b\"/>\n  </svg>"],["Identify the cable/connector shown in the image.",["DisplayPort","Molex","Coaxial (RG-6)","Fiber Optic (SC/LC/ST)"],1,"This is Molex: 4-pin, keyed on two corners. Speed: N/A (power only). Max distance: Limited by internal case routing. Used for: Legacy power connector for older hard drives, optical drives, and case fans; largely replaced by SATA power.","Hardware","<svg viewBox=\"0 0 160 110\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n    <path d=\"M40 32 L120 32 L120 78 L52 78 L40 66 Z\" fill=\"#facc15\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"58\" cy=\"55\" r=\"6\" fill=\"#1e293b\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"80\" cy=\"55\" r=\"6\" fill=\"#1e293b\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"102\" cy=\"55\" r=\"6\" fill=\"#1e293b\"/>\n  </svg>"],["Identify the printer type shown in the image.",["Laser Printer","Thermal Printer","Impact (Dot-Matrix) Printer","3D Printer"],0,"This is a Laser Printer. Uses static electricity and a laser to draw an image on a rotating drum, which attracts toner powder. The toner is transferred to paper and permanently bonded with heat and pressure. Common use: High-volume, fast, low-cost-per-page printing for offices; produces crisp text.","Hardware","<svg viewBox=\"0 0 160 110\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n    <rect x=\"25\" y=\"45\" width=\"110\" height=\"45\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#334155\"/>\n    <rect x=\"35\" y=\"30\" width=\"90\" height=\"20\" rx=\"2\" fill=\"#475569\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"80\" cy=\"67\" r=\"16\" fill=\"#3b82f6\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"80\" cy=\"67\" r=\"6\" fill=\"#0f1729\"/>\n    <rect x=\"30\" y=\"75\" width=\"18\" height=\"12\" rx=\"2\" fill=\"#facc15\"/>\n  </svg>"],["Identify the printer type shown in the image.",["Laser Printer","Thermal Printer","3D Printer","Inkjet Printer"],3,"This is a Inkjet Printer. Sprays microscopic droplets of liquid ink directly onto paper. Thermal (bubble jet) inkjets heat ink to form a vapor bubble that ejects a droplet; piezoelectric inkjets flex a crystal to eject the droplet instead. Common use: Photo-quality color printing and lower-volume home/small-office use.","Hardware","<svg viewBox=\"0 0 160 110\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n    <rect x=\"25\" y=\"50\" width=\"110\" height=\"38\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#334155\"/>\n    <rect x=\"35\" y=\"34\" width=\"90\" height=\"18\" rx=\"2\" fill=\"#475569\"/>\n    <rect x=\"55\" y=\"60\" width=\"50\" height=\"10\" rx=\"2\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"60\" cy=\"80\" r=\"6\" fill=\"#06b6d4\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"76\" cy=\"80\" r=\"6\" fill=\"#ec4899\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"92\" cy=\"80\" r=\"6\" fill=\"#facc15\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"108\" cy=\"80\" r=\"6\" fill=\"#1e293b\"/>\n  </svg>"],["Identify the printer type shown in the image.",["Inkjet Printer","Impact (Dot-Matrix) Printer","Thermal Printer","Laser Printer"],2,"This is a Thermal Printer. The print head selectively heats chemically-treated thermal paper, which darkens at the heated points to form the image or text. Common use: Receipt printers, shipping labels, and point-of-sale systems where speed and low maintenance matter more than print longevity (thermal prints fade over time).","Hardware","<svg viewBox=\"0 0 160 110\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n    <rect x=\"35\" y=\"40\" width=\"90\" height=\"40\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#334155\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"80\" cy=\"35\" r=\"18\" fill=\"#f1f5f9\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"80\" cy=\"35\" r=\"6\" fill=\"#94a3b8\"/>\n    <rect x=\"65\" y=\"82\" width=\"30\" height=\"10\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/>\n    <path d=\"M55 92 q5 6 10 0 q5 6 10 0 q5 6 10 0 q5 6 10 0\" stroke=\"#fb923c\" stroke-width=\"3\" fill=\"none\"/>\n  </svg>"],["Identify the printer type shown in the image.",["Thermal Printer","Inkjet Printer","Laser Printer","Impact (Dot-Matrix) Printer"],3,"This is a Impact (Dot-Matrix) Printer. Pins in the print head strike an ink ribbon against the paper, physically impacting it to form characters out of dots. Common use: Multi-part carbonless forms (e.g., invoices, packing slips) where the physical impact creates copies on all layers at once; still used in some warehouses and industrial settings.","Hardware","<svg viewBox=\"0 0 160 110\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n    <rect x=\"25\" y=\"42\" width=\"110\" height=\"45\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#334155\"/>\n    <rect x=\"60\" y=\"46\" width=\"40\" height=\"36\" rx=\"3\" fill=\"#475569\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"68.0\" cy=\"52.0\" r=\"2.5\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"76.0\" cy=\"52.0\" r=\"2.5\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"84.0\" cy=\"52.0\" r=\"2.5\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"68.0\" cy=\"60.0\" r=\"2.5\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"76.0\" cy=\"60.0\" r=\"2.5\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"84.0\" cy=\"60.0\" r=\"2.5\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"68.0\" cy=\"68.0\" r=\"2.5\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"76.0\" cy=\"68.0\" r=\"2.5\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/><circle cx=\"84.0\" cy=\"68.0\" r=\"2.5\" fill=\"#e2e8f0\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"30\" cy=\"55\" r=\"8\" fill=\"#dc2626\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"130\" cy=\"55\" r=\"8\" fill=\"#dc2626\"/>\n  </svg>"],["Identify the printer type shown in the image.",["3D Printer","Thermal Printer","Inkjet Printer","Laser Printer"],0,"This is a 3D Printer. FDM (Fused Deposition Modeling) printers melt plastic filament and deposit it layer by layer to build a 3D object; resin printers cure liquid resin with light, layer by layer. Common use: Prototyping, custom parts, and increasingly common in schools and small businesses.","Hardware","<svg viewBox=\"0 0 160 110\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n    <rect x=\"35\" y=\"20\" width=\"90\" height=\"8\" fill=\"#475569\"/>\n    <rect x=\"38\" y=\"20\" width=\"4\" height=\"65\" fill=\"#475569\"/>\n    <rect x=\"118\" y=\"20\" width=\"4\" height=\"65\" fill=\"#475569\"/>\n    <rect x=\"60\" y=\"35\" width=\"14\" height=\"10\" fill=\"#3b82f6\"/>\n    <rect x=\"45\" y=\"80\" width=\"70\" height=\"8\" rx=\"2\" fill=\"#94a3b8\"/>\n    <rect x=\"65\" y=\"65\" width=\"30\" height=\"6\" fill=\"#fb923c\"/>\n    <rect x=\"68\" y=\"58\" width=\"24\" height=\"6\" fill=\"#fb923c\"/>\n    <rect x=\"71\" y=\"51\" width=\"18\" height=\"6\" fill=\"#fb923c\"/>\n  </svg>"],["Scenario: A customer's printed pages are much lighter than usual, or (on a laser printer) parts of the page look inconsistently light.",["Low toner/ink, or a worn/misaligned charging roller or drum","The printer's IP address changed","The paper tray is the wrong size","The USB cable is too long"],0,"The most likely cause is: Low toner/ink, or (on laser printers) a worn/misaligned charging roller or drum.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["Scenario: A customer's printouts have consistent vertical streaks running down the page.",["A scratched/dirty drum (laser) or a clogged/dirty print head (inkjet)","The printer needs a firmware update","The document has too many images","The print spooler service is disabled"],0,"The most likely cause is: A scratched or dirty drum (laser) or a clogged/dirty print head (inkjet).","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["Scenario: The same faint ghost image appears repeatedly at a fixed interval down every printed page.",["The drum isn't being fully cleaned or discharged each imaging cycle","The paper is loaded upside down","The printer driver is missing","The network cable is unplugged"],0,"The most likely cause is: The drum isn't being fully cleaned or discharged each cycle - look for damage at intervals matching the drum's circumference.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["Scenario: A printer keeps jamming paper on nearly every print job.",["Worn or dirty pickup/feed rollers, damp paper, or a foreign object in the paper path","The toner cartridge is a third-party brand","The printer is set to duplex mode","The Wi-Fi signal is weak"],0,"The most likely cause is: Worn or dirty pickup/feed rollers, damp or damaged paper, or a foreign object in the paper path.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["Scenario: A print job comes out as pages of random symbols instead of the intended document.",["A wrong, corrupt, or outdated print driver","The paper size is set to Legal instead of Letter","The toner cartridge is empty","The printer is out of network range"],0,"The most likely cause is: Wrong, corrupt, or outdated print driver.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["Scenario: Multiple users report their print jobs are stuck and never print, even though the printer shows as online.",["The print spooler service has hung and needs to be restarted","The printer's fuser is overheating","The USB cable is unplugged","The paper tray is empty"],0,"The most likely cause is: The print spooler service has hung and typically needs to be restarted.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["Scenario: An inkjet printer's colors look faded or washed out even with new cartridges installed.",["The printer needs a print head alignment/cleaning cycle","The printer is using the wrong driver","The power cable is loose","The paper is too thick"],0,"The most likely cause is: Low/empty ink cartridge, or the printer needs a head-alignment/cleaning cycle (inkjet).","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["Scenario: A small office wants any computer on their network to print directly to a shared printer using its own IP address, with the most reliable connection possible. Which connection type best fits this need?",["Ethernet","Bluetooth","USB","Lightning"],0,"Wired network connection giving the printer its own IP address, so any device on the network can print to it directly and reliably.","Networking"],["Scenario: A user wants to print a document from their phone to a nearby printer without connecting to any Wi-Fi network. Which connection type best fits this need?",["Bluetooth","Ethernet","Print Server","SATA"],0,"Short-range direct wireless pairing between a device and printer without a network; common for compact/portable printers.","Networking"],["Scenario: A company wants one central system to manage the print queue and share several printers across hundreds of employees on the network. Which connection type best fits this need?",["Print Server","USB","Bluetooth","Coaxial"],0,"A dedicated server (or NAS/router with print-server functionality) manages the print queue and shares one or more printers across many network users.","Networking"],["Scenario: A user wants to print directly from their tablet to a printer over Wi-Fi without installing a traditional printer driver. Which connection type best fits this need?",["Cloud/Mobile Printing","SATA","Molex","RJ-11"],0,"Services like AirPrint or vendor cloud-print apps let phones and tablets send print jobs over Wi-Fi or the internet without installing a traditional driver.","Networking"],["Scenario: A home user has only one computer and wants the simplest possible direct connection to their new printer, with no network setup at all. Which connection type best fits this need?",["USB","Print Server","Ethernet","Fiber Optic"],0,"Direct wired connection from a single computer to the printer; simple, no network configuration needed, but only one device can print at a time without sharing.","Networking"],["Scenario: A printer needs to be placed somewhere a network cable can't easily reach, but the location still has a strong wireless signal. Which connection type best fits this need?",["Wi-Fi","USB","SATA","Molex"],0,"Wireless network connection; convenient for placement but can be less reliable than Ethernet in busy or interference-prone environments.","Networking"],["What does a computer's power supply unit primarily do?",["Convert AC power from the wall into regulated DC power for components","Store data during a shutdown","Cool the CPU using liquid coolant","Boost the strength of a Wi-Fi signal"],0,"The PSU takes high-voltage AC from the wall outlet and converts/regulates it into the low-voltage DC (12V, 5V, 3.3V) that the motherboard, CPU, and drives actually run on. Without this conversion, no internal component could receive usable power.","Hardware"],["Why do technicians need to worry about electrostatic discharge (ESD) around open computer hardware?",["A static shock too small to feel can silently damage chips like RAM or the CPU","It causes case fans to spin faster than normal","It automatically voids the manufacturer's warranty","It only ever affects laptop batteries"],0,"ESD can destroy delicate circuitry inside a CPU, RAM module, or motherboard even when the discharge is too small for a person to notice. Anti-static wrist straps and mats are used specifically to bleed off this static before it reaches sensitive components.","Operational Procedures"],["A workstation needs protection from voltage spikes, brownouts, and a total power outage all at once. Which combination covers all three?",["A surge protector, a voltage regulator, and a UPS together","A surge protector by itself","A longer power cable","A second PSU wired in parallel"],0,"Each device covers a different threat: a surge protector blocks sudden spikes, a voltage regulator smooths out brownouts and dips, and a UPS provides battery backup during a full outage so the system can be saved and shut down safely.","Hardware"],["Which 80 Plus certification tier wastes the least energy as heat?",["Titanium","Bronze","White","Silver"],0,"80 Plus Titanium is the highest efficiency tier, reaching up to roughly 94% efficiency at 50% load. Higher efficiency means less wasted electricity and less heat generated inside the case.","Hardware"],["On an older PSU with a manual 110V/220V voltage selector switch, what happens if it's left on the wrong setting for your region?",["The PSU can fail outright and potentially damage other components","Nothing - modern PSUs silently auto-correct regardless of the switch","The case fans will spin in reverse","Only the RGB lighting is affected"],0,"Manual-switch PSUs must be set to match local mains voltage. Getting it wrong can starve the system of power (won't boot) or overload the PSU, risking a short circuit or fire. Modern Active PFC PSUs sense voltage automatically and don't have this switch.","Hardware"],["A PSU's core job inside a desktop is best described as:",["Stepping down and rectifying AC power into usable DC power","Managing which programs launch at startup","Storing the motherboard's BIOS settings","Generating the system's Wi-Fi signal"],0,"Every internal component - motherboard, CPU, RAM, drives - needs regulated DC power to operate. The PSU's entire purpose is that AC-to-DC conversion; without it none of those parts would receive correct power.","Hardware"],["A PC won't power on and there's a burnt smell coming from inside the case. What should a technician inspect first?",["The power supply, for damage or a short circuit","The desktop wallpaper setting","The mouse pointer sensitivity","Installed browser extensions"],0,"A burnt smell paired with a system that won't power on strongly points to an electrical failure, most often the PSU. Physically inspecting it for scorch marks, bulging, or a burnt odor helps confirm whether it needs replacement before troubleshooting further.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["Voltage is often explained to beginners with a plumbing analogy. Which plumbing concept does voltage most resemble?",["Water pressure","Pipe diameter","Water color","Drain speed"],0,"Just as water pressure pushes water through pipes, voltage is the electrical \"push\" that drives current through a circuit. It's a common teaching analogy for people new to electrical concepts.","Hardware"],["Which three connectors deliver power (not data) to components inside a desktop PC?",["24-pin ATX, SATA power, and Molex","RJ-45, HDMI, and DisplayPort","SATA data, USB-C, and Ethernet","PS/2, VGA, and Molex"],0,"The 24-pin ATX connector powers the motherboard, SATA power connectors feed drives, and Molex handles some legacy/auxiliary devices. RJ-45, HDMI, and DisplayPort are all data/video connectors, not power connectors.","Hardware"],["A gamer installs a 250-watt graphics card into a system with only a 300-watt PSU, and the PC shuts down under load. What's the most likely explanation?",["The power supply can't reliably meet the combined system demand","The graphics driver needs to be updated","The monitor's refresh rate is set too high","The case fans are spinning too slowly"],0,"When total power draw approaches or exceeds what a PSU can safely deliver, the system may shut down to protect the hardware, especially under sustained load like gaming. A higher-wattage PSU with more headroom is the fix.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["Which case style is the best fit for a high-end workstation packing multiple GPUs and heavy-duty cooling?",["Full-Tower","Small Form Factor (SFF)","All-in-one (AIO)","Slimline desktop"],0,"Full-Tower cases offer the most internal volume of any consumer chassis, supporting multiple GPUs, elaborate cooling loops, and E-ATX motherboards - ideal for rendering, gaming, or scientific workloads.","Hardware"],["Compared to a Full-Tower case, what's the main selling point of a Mid-Tower?",["It's noticeably more portable and space-efficient","It supports more PCIe slots than any Full-Tower","It's the only case type that supports liquid cooling","It requires no cable management at all"],0,"Mid-Towers trade some of a Full-Tower's expansion room for a smaller, more manageable footprint, while still fitting standard ATX boards and enough drives/cooling for most builds - a popular middle ground.","Hardware"],["Why does good cable management matter inside a PC case?",["It keeps airflow paths clear, improving cooling efficiency","It increases the CPU's clock speed","It prevents the operating system from crashing","It reduces how many power cables the PSU needs"],0,"Loose, tangled cables can physically block airflow between intake and exhaust fans, causing components to run hotter. Tidy routing keeps air moving efficiently and also makes future maintenance easier.","Hardware"],["Which case format is standard in data centers and enterprise server rooms?",["Server/Rackmount","Full-Tower","Small Form Factor (SFF)","Mini-ITX cube case"],0,"Rackmount cases are measured in rack units (U) and are built for 24/7 operation, typically featuring hot-swappable drives and redundant power supplies - designed for density and reliability over aesthetics.","Hardware"],["A student wants a compact gaming PC that still moves air well. Which case type fits best?",["Small Form Factor (SFF)","Full-Tower","Server/Rackmount","Open-air test bench"],0,"SFF cases prioritize a small footprint while still supporting capable hardware, often using clever intake/exhaust placement or compatible liquid cooling to keep airflow reasonable despite the tight space.","Hardware"],["Which motherboard form factor generally offers the most PCIe expansion slots?",["E-ATX","Mini-ITX","Mini-STX","Micro-ATX"],0,"Extended ATX (E-ATX) boards are physically larger than standard ATX, giving manufacturers room for more PCIe slots - useful for servers, workstations, and multi-GPU builds.","Hardware"],["Which motherboard form factor is the go-to choice for a space-saving home theater PC?",["Mini-ITX","E-ATX","ATX","Server/Rackmount"],0,"Mini-ITX is the smallest common motherboard form factor, typically offering just one expansion slot, purpose-built for compact builds where physical space is the priority.","Hardware"],["Compared to Micro-ATX, what does a full ATX motherboard mainly offer?",["More PCIe expansion slots","A smaller physical footprint","Lower manufacturing cost","Built-in liquid cooling"],0,"ATX boards are larger than Micro-ATX and use that extra space for additional PCIe slots, giving more room to add graphics cards, sound cards, or RAID controllers later.","Hardware"],["Which motherboard size is most common in business desktops because it balances footprint and expansion?",["Micro-ATX","E-ATX","Mini-STX","Full-Tower-only ATX"],0,"Micro-ATX typically supports up to four expansion slots while staying compact and inexpensive, which fits office desktops that need basic expandability without the bulk of a full ATX board.","Hardware"],["Why might someone pick a Mini-STX motherboard over a Mini-ITX board?",["Mini-STX usually keeps a socketed, upgradeable CPU","Mini-STX supports more RAM slots than any other form factor","Mini-STX is physically larger, allowing more airflow","Mini-STX is the only form factor that supports Wi-Fi"],0,"Ultra-compact Mini-ITX systems often solder the CPU in place with no upgrade path, while Mini-STX boards typically keep a socketed CPU, letting users upgrade the processor later despite the small size.","Hardware"],["Which front-panel case connector is responsible for actually turning the PC on when you press the button?",["Power Switch (PWR_SW)","HD Audio header","USB 3.0 header","Reset header"],0,"Pressing the case's power button sends a signal through the PWR_SW connector to the motherboard, telling it to begin the boot process. Without this connection, pressing the button does nothing.","Hardware"],["Which motherboard header should front-panel USB 3.0 ports be connected to?",["The dedicated USB 3.0 header (usually blue)","The HD Audio header","The PWR_SW header","The SATA power header"],0,"USB 3.0 headers are electrically and physically different from USB 2.0 headers and support much higher transfer speeds. Plugging a USB 3.0 cable into a USB 2.0 header limits speed or may not work at all.","Hardware"],["What does the HD Audio header on a motherboard actually enable?",["Sound through the case's front-panel headphone/mic jacks","Faster boot times","RGB lighting synchronization","Wi-Fi connectivity"],0,"The HD Audio header connects the case's front headphone and microphone jacks to the motherboard, letting users plug in headsets without reaching around to the back of the PC.","Hardware"],["Why should a technician always check the motherboard's manual before wiring up front-panel case headers?",["It shows exact header locations and prevents damaging miswires","It's only needed for gaming motherboards","It replaces the need for a power supply","It's required by the manufacturer's warranty terms only"],0,"Header layouts differ between motherboards. The manual shows exactly where power, reset, USB, and audio headers are and how they're keyed, preventing mistakes like reversed pins that can cause failures or damage.","Hardware"],["Which type of RGB header lets you control each individual LED separately for effects like color-cycling?",["ARGB (Addressable RGB)","Standard RGB","HD Audio RGB","PWM RGB"],0,"Standard RGB headers change every connected LED to the same color at once. ARGB headers address each LED individually, enabling effects like rainbow patterns or chasing lights across a strip.","Hardware"],["Which chipset component historically handled fast communication between the CPU, RAM, and graphics card?",["The Northbridge","The Southbridge","The Platform Controller Hub","The VRM"],0,"On older motherboards, the Northbridge managed high-speed traffic between the CPU, RAM, and GPU. That functionality has since been absorbed directly into modern CPUs, simplifying motherboard design.","Hardware"],["What is the main job of PCIe lanes on a motherboard?",["Providing high-speed data paths between the CPU and expansion cards","Regulating voltage sent to the CPU","Cooling the chipset","Storing firmware settings"],0,"PCIe lanes act like dedicated data highways connecting expansion cards - GPUs, NVMe drives, network cards - to the CPU. More available lanes generally means more bandwidth for that device.","Hardware"],["Which chipset-related feature lets a user push a CPU to run faster than its factory-rated speed?",["Overclocking","Underclocking","Wear-leveling","Zero-touch deployment"],0,"Overclocking increases CPU clock speed beyond factory specification for extra performance, at the cost of generating more heat - which is why it requires solid cooling to remain stable.","Hardware"],["What replaced the old Northbridge/Southbridge chipset design in most modern motherboards?",["A Platform Controller Hub (PCH)","A secondary CPU socket","An onboard GPU exclusively","A dedicated RAID controller"],0,"Modern systems moved fast tasks like memory access directly into the CPU, while a Platform Controller Hub (PCH) now manages slower functions like USB ports and storage - reducing bottlenecks versus the old two-chip design.","Hardware"],["What can happen if you install an NVMe SSD into a motherboard slot that shares PCIe lanes with another slot?",["Other devices sharing those lanes may see reduced bandwidth","The motherboard will refuse to boot entirely","The NVMe drive will run at double its rated speed","It will automatically disable the onboard chipset"],0,"Some motherboard slots share a limited pool of PCIe lanes. Populating one can reduce the lanes available to another slot (like a GPU or SATA port), lowering performance without causing outright failure - checking the manual for shared-lane slots avoids surprises.","Hardware"],["Which storage connector offers the fastest data transfer speeds available on a modern motherboard?",["PCIe NVMe (M.2)","SATA III","USB 3.0","IDE/PATA"],0,"SATA tops out around 6 Gbps, but PCIe NVMe M.2 drives can exceed 7,000 MB/s - dramatically faster since they connect through PCIe lanes rather than the older SATA interface.","Hardware"],["What does a USB header on a motherboard actually connect?",["The case's front-panel USB ports to the motherboard","The CPU to the RAM","The PSU to the GPU","The chipset to the BIOS chip"],0,"USB headers give the front (or top) panel USB ports on a case a path back to the motherboard, so users can plug in flash drives and peripherals without reaching around to the rear I/O panel.","Hardware"],["A motherboard has an open PCIe x16 slot. What type of card is that slot almost always meant for?",["A graphics card (GPU)","A sound card","A Wi-Fi adapter","An NVMe expansion adapter"],0,"PCIe x16 slots provide the most bandwidth and are physically the largest, reserved primarily for graphics cards. Smaller x1 slots typically handle lower-bandwidth cards like Wi-Fi or sound adapters.","Hardware"],["What's the practical difference between an RGB header and an ARGB header?",["ARGB allows per-LED control; standard RGB changes all LEDs together","RGB is digital while ARGB is analog","ARGB only works with case fans, never LED strips","RGB headers require more power than ARGB"],0,"Standard RGB headers push one color to an entire strip at once. ARGB (Addressable RGB) headers can control each LED individually, enabling effects like rainbow gradients or chase patterns.","Hardware"],["Before installing a new storage drive, why should a technician check the motherboard's manual for M.2 slot details?",["Different M.2 slots may support only SATA, only NVMe, or both","The manual is only needed for laptop motherboards","M.2 slots are universally identical across all boards","It's required to activate the PSU's warranty"],0,"Not every M.2 slot on a board supports the same protocols - some are SATA-only, some NVMe-only, some both. Checking the manual first avoids installing an incompatible drive that won't be recognized.","Hardware"],["Which expansion slot is the standard choice for a high-performance graphics card?",["PCIe x16","PCIe x1","M.2 Key E","SATA Express"],0,"PCIe x16 slots deliver the most lanes/bandwidth of any common expansion slot, matching the high-speed data needs of a modern GPU for gaming, rendering, or compute workloads.","Hardware"],["A motherboard has 16 total PCIe lanes and two PCIe devices are installed. What typically happens to each device's bandwidth?",["Each device may get fewer lanes (e.g. split to x8/x8) and run slower","Bandwidth is unaffected since lanes are unlimited","The second device is automatically disabled","The motherboard permanently reassigns all 16 lanes to one device"],0,"PCIe lanes are a shared, finite resource. Installing two lane-hungry devices on a board with limited lanes can force the board to split availability (e.g., x8/x8 instead of x16), somewhat reducing performance for both.","Hardware"],["Which expansion card type is built specifically for capturing and streaming external video sources?",["A capture card","A sound card","A RAID controller","A network interface card"],0,"Capture cards ingest video from external sources like consoles or cameras and pass it to the PC over a high-speed PCIe connection, which is essential for low-lag recording and streaming.","Hardware"],["What does an M.2 Wi-Fi card primarily add to a desktop PC?",["Wireless networking and Bluetooth connectivity","Extra SATA ports","Additional USB-C ports","A hardware RAID controller"],0,"Small M.2 Wi-Fi/Bluetooth modules plug into a Key-E or A+E M.2 slot to add wireless capability to a desktop that lacks it natively, often requiring external antennas for good reception.","Networking"],["Before installing any expansion card, why should a technician consult the motherboard manual?",["To confirm the correct slot, adequate bandwidth, and proper orientation","Because expansion cards cannot be returned once opened","To find the Wi-Fi password","Because all expansion cards are installed identically"],0,"Slot layouts, bandwidth limits, and physical keying vary by motherboard. Checking the manual first ensures the card goes in the correct slot, gets enough bandwidth, and is installed correctly and safely.","Hardware"],["What is the core job of BIOS/UEFI firmware when a PC first powers on?",["Initialize hardware and hand off control to the OS","Render the desktop wallpaper","Manage installed application updates","Encrypt the hard drive automatically"],0,"BIOS/UEFI is the very first code that runs on power-on. It checks and initializes core hardware (CPU, memory, storage) before passing control to the bootloader and eventually the operating system.","Operating Systems"],["What's a genuine advantage UEFI has over traditional BIOS?",["Support for larger drives and stronger security features like Secure Boot","It eliminates the need for a power supply","It only works with 32-bit operating systems","It removes the need for any storage drive"],0,"UEFI supports GPT partitioning (drives over 2TB) and adds modern protections like Secure Boot and TPM integration, which legacy BIOS never had - improving both compatibility and security.","Operating Systems"],["Which firmware type does a modern 64-bit OS like Windows 11 require?",["UEFI","Legacy BIOS","CSM-only mode","MBR firmware"],0,"Windows 11 requires UEFI because features it depends on - Secure Boot and TPM - aren't available under Legacy BIOS. UEFI also boots faster and supports more modern hardware.","Operating Systems"],["Installing 32-bit Windows 7 on a modern UEFI motherboard usually requires enabling what setting?",["Legacy Boot / Compatibility Support Module (CSM)","Secure Boot Enforcement","TPM Passthrough","Fast Boot Only mode"],0,"Many older 32-bit operating systems can't boot natively under pure UEFI mode. Enabling Legacy Boot/CSM makes the board emulate old BIOS behavior so older install media will work.","Operating Systems"],["A PC is running Windows 10 on Legacy BIOS/MBR. What must happen before it can be upgraded to Windows 11?",["Convert the drive from MBR to GPT and enable UEFI","Simply download the Windows 11 installer and run it","Reduce the drive to a single 2TB partition","Disable the CPU's cache memory"],0,"Windows 11 requires a GPT-partitioned drive running under UEFI. Since Legacy BIOS uses MBR, the drive must be converted and UEFI mode enabled in firmware settings before the upgrade can proceed.","Operating Systems"],["Which CPU component is specifically responsible for handling decimal/floating-point math?",["The FPU (Floating Point Unit)","The ALU (Arithmetic Logic Unit)","The L1 cache","The memory controller"],0,"The FPU handles decimal-based calculations needed for tasks like 3D rendering and scientific simulation, while the ALU is limited to integer math and logic operations.","Hardware"],["What's the main practical benefit of x64 CPUs over older x86 CPUs?",["They can address far more RAM and run 64-bit software more efficiently","They physically use less electricity in every case","They are only compatible with Linux","They eliminate the need for any cooling"],0,"x64 processors can address vastly more memory than 32-bit x86 chips and run 64-bit applications more efficiently, while still supporting most 32-bit software for backward compatibility.","Hardware"],["Which CPU architecture dominates smartphones and tablets due to its power efficiency?",["ARM","x86","x64-only desktop chips","IA-64"],0,"ARM's simplified instruction set prioritizes low power draw over raw performance-per-core, which is exactly what's needed in battery-powered mobile devices and embedded systems.","Mobile Devices"],["What's the main purpose of CPU cache memory?",["Speed up access to frequently used data by sitting closer to the CPU than RAM","Permanently store the operating system","Replace the need for a hard drive","Cool the CPU during heavy workloads"],0,"Cache sits physically closer to the CPU core than main RAM and holds frequently accessed data, cutting down wait times and bridging the speed gap between the ultra-fast CPU and comparatively slower RAM.","Hardware"],["How do a process and a thread differ?",["A process is a running program; a thread is a sub-task running within it","A thread is a running program; a process is a sub-task within it","They are two names for the exact same thing","A process only exists on servers, never desktops"],0,"A process represents an entire running application. Threads are smaller units of work inside that process that can run concurrently, which is especially useful on multicore CPUs handling several tasks at once.","Operating Systems"],["Which CPU socket design is standard on most modern Intel desktop processors?",["LGA (Land Grid Array)","PGA (Pin Grid Array)","BGA (Ball Grid Array) exclusively","ZIF-only sockets with no pins anywhere"],0,"In LGA sockets, the pins live on the motherboard itself while the CPU has flat contact pads, which helps protect the more expensive CPU from bent-pin damage compared to older pin-on-CPU designs.","Hardware"],["What's the main benefit of a ZIF (Zero Insertion Force) CPU socket?",["The CPU can be seated with no pressure, then locked with a lever","It permanently glues the CPU to the socket","It doubles the CPU's clock speed","It removes the need for thermal paste"],0,"ZIF sockets let a technician drop the CPU into place without pressing down, then secure it with a locking lever - reducing the risk of bent pins or cracked dies during installation.","Hardware"],["Where would you typically find a motherboard with multiple CPU sockets?",["Servers and data centers","Budget home desktops","Entry-level laptops","Smartphones"],0,"Multi-socket boards let more than one physical CPU work together, which is used in servers and data centers running heavy workloads like virtualization, hosting, or large-scale simulation.","Hardware"],["A PC powers on (fans spin) but never POSTs. What's the most likely culprit?",["An improperly seated CPU or RAM module","A missing operating system","An outdated web browser","A disconnected monitor cable only"],0,"When a system powers on but never completes POST, a loose or improperly seated CPU or RAM stick is one of the most common causes, since it breaks communication before POST can even run.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["A computer keeps freezing specifically during CPU-intensive tasks. What should be checked first?",["Thermal paste application and CPU temperatures","The desktop background image","The keyboard layout language","The number of browser tabs open"],0,"Freezing under load is a classic overheating symptom. Poor thermal paste application or a failing cooler can let temperatures spike, triggering throttling or a protective shutdown - checking temps is the logical first step.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["Which motherboard component regulates and delivers correct voltage to the CPU and RAM?",["The Voltage Regulator Module (VRM)","The Southbridge","The chipset heatsink","The BIOS chip"],0,"The VRM converts and steadies incoming power from the PSU into the precise voltages the CPU and RAM require. A failing VRM can cause instability, boot failures, or even hardware damage from bad voltage.","Hardware"],["What is a POST card used for during motherboard troubleshooting?",["Displaying error codes that reveal hardware failures before the OS loads","Boosting Wi-Fi signal during boot","Adding extra RAM slots","Replacing a failed graphics card"],0,"A POST card plugs into a PCI/PCIe slot and shows numeric codes during startup, helping a technician pinpoint a failing component (RAM, CPU, chipset) even on systems that give no beeps or video output.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["A motherboard has a burning smell and visibly swollen capacitors. What's the appropriate next step?",["Replace the motherboard","Reapply thermal paste to the capacitors","Reformat the hard drive","Update the graphics driver"],0,"Swollen or burnt capacitors indicate serious, typically irreversible electrical damage. Attempting a repair is risky and rarely cost-effective; replacing the board is the safe path forward.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["Which RAM form factor is designed for laptops and other compact systems?",["SO-DIMM","Full-size DIMM","ECC UDIMM","RDIMM"],0,"SO-DIMM (Small Outline DIMM) modules are physically smaller than standard desktop DIMMs to fit laptop and mini-PC form factors, and the two are not interchangeable.","Hardware"],["Which DDR generation first introduced the 288-pin DIMM layout?",["DDR4","DDR3","DDR2","DDR5"],0,"DDR4 moved to a 288-pin module, up from DDR3's 240 pins, improving both speed and power efficiency - the differing pin count and notch position also prevents accidentally installing the wrong generation.","Hardware"],["What happens if you try to install DDR4 RAM into a motherboard that only supports DDR3?",["It physically won't fit due to a different notch position","It works fine but runs at DDR3 speeds","It fits but damages the CPU immediately","The motherboard automatically upgrades to support DDR4"],0,"Each DDR generation has a unique notch position on the module that's deliberately incompatible with other generations' slots, physically preventing an incorrect (and potentially damaging) installation.","Hardware"],["Where in Windows can you quickly check how much RAM is installed and its speed?",["Task Manager's Performance tab","The Recycle Bin properties","Notepad's file menu","The desktop screensaver settings"],0,"Task Manager's Performance tab shows real-time memory details including total capacity, speed, and slot usage, making it a fast way to confirm whether RAM is installed correctly or needs an upgrade.","Operating Systems"],["What's a key advantage DDR5 has over earlier DDR generations?",["Significantly higher speeds and bandwidth","It's the only DDR generation compatible with every motherboard","It requires no motherboard support at all","It uses the exact same pin layout as DDR3 for easy swaps"],0,"DDR5 offers a substantial bandwidth and speed jump over DDR4, benefiting demanding workloads like gaming, video editing, and AI tasks - but it requires a motherboard specifically built to support it.","Hardware"],["Which RAM type is designed to automatically detect and correct minor memory errors?",["ECC RAM","SO-DIMM RAM","Dual-channel RAM","Overclocked RAM"],0,"ECC (Error-Correcting Code) RAM catches and fixes small memory errors on the fly, which is why it's favored in servers and workstations where data integrity is critical - though it needs ECC-compatible hardware.","Hardware"],["What's the main performance benefit of running RAM in dual-channel mode instead of single-channel?",["Increased memory bandwidth between RAM and CPU","Lower RAM temperature","Automatic overclocking of the CPU","Free upgrade to ECC support"],0,"Dual-channel mode uses two RAM modules together to roughly double the communication bandwidth to the CPU, improving performance in multitasking and demanding applications - but the sticks must be in the correct matched slots.","Hardware"],["A newly built PC only recognizes half of its installed RAM. What's the most likely cause?",["The RAM sticks are installed in the wrong motherboard slots","The power supply is too weak for RAM","The RAM is a counterfeit product","Windows has a hidden RAM limit of 8GB"],0,"Many motherboards require specific slot pairings to enable dual- or quad-channel mode. Sticks placed in the wrong slots may still boot the system but leave part of the memory unrecognized or running in single-channel mode.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["How can you confirm in Windows that RAM is actually running in dual-channel mode?",["Check Task Manager's Performance → Memory tab","Open the Control Panel's Fonts folder","Look at the taskbar clock properties","Check the printer queue"],0,"Task Manager's Memory view under the Performance tab reports whether the system is operating in single- or dual-channel mode, giving a quick confirmation without third-party tools.","Operating Systems"],["A freshly installed RAM stick isn't being detected by the system at all. What should be checked first?",["Reseat the module and confirm correct slot placement in the manual","Immediately RMA the motherboard","Replace the CPU","Reinstall the operating system"],0,"Undetected RAM is most often simply not fully seated, or installed in an unsupported slot combination. Reseating it carefully and checking the motherboard manual for the proper slots is the correct first step.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["What does the actuator arm do inside a traditional hard disk drive?",["Moves the read/write heads across the spinning platters","Spins the platters at high speed","Converts AC power to DC for the drive","Compresses stored data automatically"],0,"The actuator arm swings the read/write heads back and forth over the spinning platters to reach the correct data location - functionally similar to a record player's needle arm, but far faster and more precise.","Hardware"],["What's a typical spindle speed for a standard desktop hard drive?",["7,200 RPM","1,200 RPM","15,000 RPM as the baseline","500 RPM"],0,"7,200 RPM is the common baseline for desktop HDDs, balancing performance and cost. Laptop drives often spin slower (like 5,400 RPM) to save power and reduce heat.","Hardware"],["Why are traditional HDDs generally more failure-prone than SSDs?",["HDDs contain moving mechanical parts that can wear out or fail","HDDs run hotter than any other PC component","HDDs cannot be formatted more than once","HDDs require twice the voltage of SSDs"],0,"Spinning platters and a moving actuator arm are mechanical parts that can wear, misalign, or break, especially from drops or heavy use. SSDs have no moving parts, making them inherently more durable.","Hardware"],["What happens to an HDD if its platters stop spinning?",["The drive becomes completely unusable until spinning resumes","Data is automatically transferred to RAM instead","Only write operations are affected, reads still work","The drive switches to SSD-style operation"],0,"An HDD's read/write heads can only access data while the platters are spinning. If the motor fails or power is lost, the drive can't move data at all, rendering it non-functional.","Hardware"],["On average, how long does a typical HDD last before it's expected to fail?",["Roughly 3-7 years","About 3-7 months","10-15 years, regardless of use","Indefinitely if never powered on"],0,"Most HDDs last somewhere in the 3-7 year range depending on heat, dust, handling, and workload. Because failure can happen with little warning, regular backups are important.","Hardware"],["What's a primary advantage SSDs have over traditional HDDs?",["Much faster read/write speeds","Lower purchase price per gigabyte","Higher spindle RPM ratings","Louder, more audible operation"],0,"SSDs use flash memory instead of spinning platters, giving them dramatically faster access and transfer speeds - translating into quicker boots, faster app loads, and snappier overall performance.","Hardware"],["What does the TRIM command do for an SSD?",["Tells the drive which data blocks are no longer in use so it can clean them up","Increases the SSD's total storage capacity","Encrypts all data on the drive automatically","Physically defragments platters like an HDD"],0,"TRIM lets the operating system inform the SSD which blocks hold deleted data, allowing the drive to reclaim and prepare those blocks ahead of future writes, keeping performance consistent over time.","Hardware"],["How does wear-leveling help extend an SSD's usable lifespan?",["It spreads write operations evenly across cells instead of repeatedly hitting the same ones","It slows down all write operations to reduce wear","It disables writes once the drive reaches 50% full","It converts write operations into read operations"],0,"Flash memory cells can only handle a limited number of write cycles. Wear-leveling distributes writes evenly across all available cells so no single area wears out prematurely, extending overall drive life.","Hardware"],["Which SSD interface offers the highest potential transfer speeds?",["NVMe","SATA III","USB 2.0","IDE/PATA"],0,"NVMe drives communicate over PCIe lanes instead of the older SATA interface, unlocking dramatically higher throughput - ideal for gaming, video editing, and large file transfers.","Hardware"],["Why do SSDs generally consume less power than HDDs?",["They have no spinning platters or moving read/write heads","They run at a fixed low voltage mandated by law","They only operate when the lid is closed on a laptop","They use smaller physical connectors"],0,"SSDs are fully electronic, storing data in flash memory chips with nothing mechanical to move. That eliminates the power draw of spinning platters and actuator motion, making them more efficient - especially valuable in laptops.","Hardware"],["What's the most common symptom pointing to failing RAM?",["Blue Screen of Death (BSOD) crashes","A cracked laptop hinge","Slow Wi-Fi speeds only","A dim keyboard backlight"],0,"Unstable or corrupted memory frequently manifests as random crashes, application errors, or full BSOD events, since the system can no longer trust the data it's reading from RAM.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["A system randomly freezes and apps close unexpectedly with no clear pattern. What's a sensible first troubleshooting step?",["Run a memory diagnostic test","Reinstall every application on the system","Replace the power supply immediately","Update the case fan firmware"],0,"These symptoms often trace back to failing RAM. A tool like Windows Memory Diagnostic or MemTest86 can confirm or rule out a memory problem quickly, before moving on to more invasive troubleshooting.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["Which built-in technology monitors a drive's health and can warn of an impending failure?",["S.M.A.R.T.","TRIM","BitLocker","ReFS"],0,"S.M.A.R.T. (Self-Monitoring, Analysis, and Reporting Technology) is built into most modern HDDs and SSDs, tracking health indicators and warning users before a drive fails outright, giving time to back up data.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["An HDD is making repeated clicking sounds and won't boot. What should the technician do?",["Back up any accessible data immediately, then replace the drive","Ignore the noise since it's cosmetic","Reformat the drive to clear the clicking","Update the drive's firmware while it's clicking"],0,"Clicking noises are a strong sign of mechanical failure inside an HDD. The priority shifts immediately to rescuing any accessible data before the drive fails completely, followed by replacement.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["A PC displays 'Operating System Not Found' at startup. What's the best first troubleshooting step?",["Check whether the boot drive is even detected in BIOS/UEFI","Immediately reinstall the operating system from scratch","Replace the power supply","Update the graphics card driver"],0,"This error usually means the firmware can't locate a drive with a bootable OS. The first move is entering BIOS/UEFI to confirm the drive is detected and correctly set as the boot device before assuming a bigger failure.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["Which USB version was the first to reach transfer speeds up to 5 Gbps?",["USB 3.0","USB 2.0","USB 1.1","USB On-The-Go"],0,"USB 3.0 introduced \"SuperSpeed\" transfers up to 5 Gbps, a massive jump over USB 2.0's 480 Mbps ceiling, making it the new standard for fast external drives and peripherals.","Hardware"],["Which USB connector type can be plugged in either orientation?",["USB Type-C","USB Type-A","Micro-USB","Mini-USB"],0,"USB-C's symmetrical design means there's no wrong way to plug it in, unlike USB-A, Micro-USB, or Mini-USB, which all require a specific orientation.","Hardware"],["What is the maximum power output supported by USB Power Delivery (USB-PD)?",["100W","15W","45W","250W"],0,"USB-PD over supported USB-C ports can deliver up to 100 watts, enough to charge many laptops and monitors through a single cable rather than needing a dedicated power brick.","Hardware"],["Which of these is NOT actually a USB feature?",["Built-in wireless data transfer","Hot-swapping devices without rebooting","Plug-and-play device recognition","Backward compatibility with older USB versions"],0,"USB is fundamentally a wired standard. Wireless transfer is handled by entirely separate technologies like Bluetooth, Wi-Fi, or NFC, not by USB itself.","Hardware"],["What does Thunderbolt add on top of what a standard USB-C port offers?",["Support for external GPUs and daisy-chaining multiple devices via PCIe","A completely different, incompatible physical connector","Wireless charging capability","Immunity to all types of cable damage"],0,"Thunderbolt shares USB-C's connector shape but layers PCIe support on top, enabling external GPU enclosures, very fast external storage, multiple 4K displays, and daisy-chaining several devices off one port.","Hardware"],["Which printer technology uses a charged drum and toner that's fused onto the page with heat?",["Laser","Inkjet","Thermal","Dot-matrix"],0,"Laser printers use an electrostatically charged drum to attract toner powder to the page, then bond it permanently using a heated fuser - producing sharp, fast output well suited to high-volume printing.","Hardware"],["What role does a print server play on a network with multiple users sharing one printer?",["It manages and queues incoming print jobs from multiple users","It physically stores paper for the printer","It converts the printer into a scanner","It encrypts documents before printing"],0,"A print server acts as a middleman, receiving print requests from many users, lining them up in a queue, and dispatching them to the printer in order - preventing conflicts in shared office environments.","Networking"],["A small office wants a new printer reachable by several users through their router, with stable, fast performance. Which connection type fits best?",["Ethernet","Bluetooth","A direct USB cable to one PC","Infrared"],0,"A wired Ethernet connection is more stable and faster than wireless options, and connecting through the router lets multiple users on the network print to it reliably.","Networking"],["Which two of the following are input peripheral devices?",["Scanner and keyboard","Printer and monitor","Speaker and printer","Monitor and speaker"],0,"Input devices send data into the computer - a keyboard sends text/commands, a scanner digitizes physical documents. Printers and monitors instead output information from the computer, making them output devices.","Hardware"],["What's the purpose of running a calibration on a laser or inkjet printer?",["It aligns toner or ink placement for accurate, sharp output","It refills the toner or ink cartridge automatically","It updates the printer's firmware over Wi-Fi","It changes the default paper size"],0,"Calibration aligns the ink or toner placement system so printed output matches the intended layout and color accuracy - without it, prints can look blurry, misaligned, or have off colors, especially in color printing.","Hardware"],["A USB keyboard suddenly stops responding. What's the first troubleshooting step?",["Check Device Manager for driver errors","Replace the motherboard","Reinstall the operating system","Swap the power supply"],0,"Device Manager quickly shows whether Windows even recognizes the keyboard and flags any driver problems. It's a fast way to rule out a software issue before assuming the hardware itself has failed.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["What's a common visible symptom of a failing graphics card?",["Flickering or visually distorted display output","The keyboard backlight turning off","The mouse cursor moving slower than usual","The system clock resetting"],0,"A degrading or overheating GPU often produces flickering, artifacting, or color distortion, especially under load like gaming or video playback - among the clearest visual signs of GPU trouble.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["Where in Windows would you adjust a monitor's resolution and refresh rate?",["Display Settings","Ease of Access Center","Sound Settings","Region and Language Settings"],0,"Windows Display Settings lets users match resolution, orientation, and refresh rate to what the connected monitor actually supports - getting this wrong can cause blurry visuals or a blank screen.","Operating Systems"],["A monitor shows 'No Signal' right after being connected to a working computer. What should be checked first?",["Whether the monitor is set to the correct input source","Whether the CPU needs to be reseated","Whether the case fans are spinning","Whether the keyboard is plugged in"],0,"Modern monitors often have several inputs (HDMI, DisplayPort, VGA). If it's set to the wrong one, it won't display anything even though the cable and PC are both working fine - switching inputs is a quick, common fix.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["What's the main purpose of case fans inside a computer?",["Maintain airflow to move heat out of the case","Increase the CPU's clock speed","Provide backup power during an outage","Store temporary system files"],0,"Case fans pull cool air in and push hot air out, keeping components like the CPU, GPU, and PSU from overheating. Without this airflow, temperatures can climb enough to cause instability or damage.","Hardware"],["What is thermal paste actually for?",["Improving heat transfer between the CPU and its cooler","Preventing dust buildup inside the case","Insulating the CPU electrically","Lubricating the cooler's fan bearing"],0,"Microscopic gaps between a CPU's surface and its cooler trap air, which conducts heat poorly. Thermal paste fills those gaps, letting heat move efficiently from the CPU into the cooler.","Hardware"],["A new liquid cooler is installed but CPU temps are still high. What should be checked first?",["Whether the radiator fans are oriented to exhaust hot air correctly","Whether the case has enough RGB lighting","Whether the mouse DPI is set correctly","Whether the monitor refresh rate matches the GPU"],0,"Radiator fan direction matters a lot - if fans are mounted backward, they fight against proper airflow instead of helping it, which can leave temperatures high even with a liquid cooler installed.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["A freshly installed CPU cooler is immediately followed by overheating. What's the most likely cause?",["Thermal paste was missing or applied incorrectly","The CPU socket type doesn't matter for cooling","The case has too many fans installed","The power supply wattage is too high"],0,"Uneven, missing, or excessive thermal paste creates poor contact between the CPU and cooler, causing hot spots and immediate overheating right after a cooler swap - proper paste application is essential.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["What advantage does a 4-pin PWM fan connector have over a 3-pin connector?",["It supports automatic speed control via Pulse Width Modulation","It physically fits more fan blades","It eliminates the need for a fan entirely","It only works with liquid coolers"],0,"4-pin PWM headers let the motherboard dynamically adjust fan speed based on temperature, increasing airflow under load and quieting down when the system is idle - something a basic 3-pin connector can't do.","Hardware"],["During which step of CompTIA's six-step troubleshooting methodology do you write down the solution for future reference?",["Document findings, actions, and outcomes","Identify the problem","Establish a theory of probable cause","Test the theory to determine the cause"],0,"Documentation is the final step, performed only after the issue is confirmed resolved. Recording the problem, the fix, and the outcome helps other technicians solve similar issues faster down the line.","Operational Procedures"],["A customer's laser-printed pages are faded even after a fresh toner cartridge was installed. What should be checked next?",["The fuser and transfer roller","The printer's Wi-Fi password","The paper tray's physical size setting","The monitor's brightness setting"],0,"If a new cartridge doesn't fix faded output, the fuser or transfer roller may be dirty or worn, preventing toner from bonding to the page properly - inspecting and replacing them if needed can restore print quality.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["Restarting which Windows service often clears stuck print jobs without a full reboot?",["Print Spooler","Windows Update","Task Scheduler","Print Server"],0,"The Print Spooler manages the queue of documents waiting to print. Restarting it clears jammed or stuck jobs without needing to reboot the whole computer - a fast, common printing fix.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["A printer is producing garbled, nonsense output. Which of these are valid troubleshooting steps?",["Update/reinstall the print driver, check spooler logs, and confirm the correct printer is selected","Only replacing the printer entirely","Only reformatting the print server's hard drive","Only restarting the monitor"],0,"Garbled output usually points to a driver or communication issue between the PC and printer. Updating/reinstalling the driver, reviewing spooler logs, and confirming the right printer is targeted are all valid diagnostic steps.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["A laptop won't boot: the screen is black and there are no startup sounds at all. What should be checked first?",["The AC adapter and power connection","The BIOS boot order","The installed antivirus software","The Wi-Fi adapter driver"],0,"Total unresponsiveness - no lights, no sound, no display - points to a power problem rather than software. Verifying the AC adapter, cable, and battery connection comes before investigating BIOS or deeper hardware issues.","Hardware and Network Troubleshooting"],["What is POST responsible for early in the boot process?",["Testing that key hardware components are functioning","Loading the desktop wallpaper","Downloading Windows updates","Encrypting the hard drive"],0,"POST (Power-On Self-Test) runs immediately after power-on, checking components like RAM, CPU, and storage. If something fails, the system alerts the user via error messages or beep codes before continuing.","Operating Systems"],["Which component is responsible for actually locating and loading the operating system into memory?",["The bootloader","The BIOS chip alone","The power supply","The chipset heatsink"],0,"After BIOS/UEFI finishes its checks, the bootloader takes over, finding the OS files on the drive and loading them into memory. Without it, the system would stall before ever reaching a desktop.","Operating Systems"],["Which of these is a genuine improvement UEFI brought over legacy BIOS?",["A graphical interface, support for drives over 2TB, and Secure Boot","The complete removal of firmware from motherboards","Mandatory 32-bit-only operation","Elimination of the need for an operating system"],0,"UEFI modernized firmware with a graphical, mouse-navigable interface, GPT support for drives larger than 2TB, and Secure Boot to block unauthorized code from loading before the OS starts.","Operating Systems"],["What happens if a PC can't find any bootable device during startup?",["It displays an error message and halts","It automatically installs a fresh copy of Windows","It boots into Safe Mode by default","It silently boots from the last known good USB drive"],0,"Without a valid bootable device - due to a disconnected drive, wrong boot order, or corruption - the firmware stops and displays an error, since it has nowhere to load an operating system from.","Operating Systems"],["What is the kernel's role once the bootloader hands off control?",["Managing hardware, drivers, and core system processes","Displaying the login screen's wallpaper","Running third-party antivirus scans","Formatting new USB drives automatically"],0,"The kernel is the OS's core, taking over from the bootloader to manage hardware communication, load drivers, and start essential system services - without it, the system couldn't talk to its own devices.","Operating Systems"],["What is the fundamental job of an operating system?",["Managing both hardware and the software running on it","Only managing printer drivers","Only providing internet connectivity","Physically cooling internal components"],0,"The OS is the middle layer between physical hardware and running software, coordinating how programs access memory, storage, and peripherals. Without it, a computer couldn't run applications at all.","Operating Systems"],["Which desktop operating system is open-source, letting anyone view and modify its underlying code?",["Linux","Windows","macOS","ChromeOS"],0,"Linux's source code is publicly available to inspect, modify, and redistribute, giving it far more customization potential than the closed-source Windows or macOS.","Operating Systems"],["What does it mean when an operating system reaches End-of-Life (EOL)?",["It stops receiving security updates from the developer","It physically stops booting on any hardware","It becomes free to license","It gains new features automatically"],0,"An EOL operating system still technically runs, but the vendor no longer issues security patches - leaving it increasingly vulnerable to malware and exploits the longer it stays in use.","Security"],["Which mobile operating system is used across the widest range of manufacturers?",["Android","iOS","iPadOS","watchOS"],0,"Android is open-source and licensed by many manufacturers - Samsung, Google, Motorola, and others - making it the most widely deployed mobile OS globally, unlike iOS which is Apple-exclusive.","Mobile Devices"],["Why does keeping an operating system updated matter?",["It improves security and overall performance","It's required to keep the case fans spinning","It automatically increases available RAM","It changes the desktop wallpaper monthly"],0,"OS updates patch security vulnerabilities that attackers could exploit and often include performance and stability improvements, helping hardware and software continue working well together.","Security"],["What's the core reason different operating systems sometimes can't fully read each other's drives?",["Each OS tends to favor its own native file system","All operating systems use the exact same file system","Hard drives physically differ based on the OS installed","USB ports are OS-specific"],0,"Windows, macOS, and Linux each default to their own file systems (NTFS, APFS, ext4). Without a shared format like exFAT or extra software, moving data between them can hit read-only access or compatibility errors.","Operating Systems"],["What's a common way to run Windows-only software on a Mac or Linux machine?",["Run it inside a virtual machine","Physically swap the motherboard","Rename the application's file extension","Disable the Mac's file system entirely"],0,"A virtual machine runs an entire separate OS instance inside the host system, letting Windows-only programs run on macOS or Linux without dual-booting or reinstalling the primary OS.","Virtualization and Cloud Computing"],["Which protocol does Windows use by default for network file and printer sharing?",["SMB","FTP","SSH","SNMP"],0,"SMB (Server Message Block) is Windows' native protocol for sharing files and printers across a network. macOS and Linux can also connect to SMB shares using compatibility tools like Samba.","Networking"],["What's a risk when moving files directly from a Linux system to a Windows system?",["The file's original permissions may not carry over correctly","The file will always be deleted automatically","Windows will refuse to read any Linux-created file","The file size will always double"],0,"Linux and Windows handle file permissions differently, so a file's original access settings can be lost or altered during transfer, potentially exposing data or restricting it incorrectly.","Operating Systems"],["Which file system handles large files across both Windows and macOS without needing extra drivers?",["exFAT","NTFS","ext4","APFS"],0,"exFAT removes FAT32's 4GB file size ceiling while remaining natively readable/writable on both Windows and macOS, making it a strong pick for external drives shared between platforms.","Operating Systems"],["Which file system is required to install and run Windows itself?",["NTFS","FAT32","exFAT","ext4"],0,"NTFS supports the permissions, journaling, and large file sizes Windows needs for its system drive - FAT32 and exFAT are fine for external storage but lack the features required for a Windows install.","Operating Systems"],["Why does FAT32 remain common on USB flash drives despite its age?",["Its wide compatibility across nearly every OS and device","It's the fastest file system available today","It supports unlimited individual file sizes","It's the only file system supporting encryption"],0,"FAT32 can be read and written by Windows, macOS, Linux, cameras, and game consoles without extra software - its main drawback is a hard 4GB limit on individual file size.","Operating Systems"],["What does APFS offer over the older HFS+ file system on Mac?",["Built-in encryption, space sharing, and snapshots","Compatibility with Windows installation media","Support for FAT32-only drives","Removal of all file permissions"],0,"APFS was designed around modern SSDs, adding strong native encryption, the ability to share free space across volumes, and snapshots for quickly saving/restoring data states - all improvements over HFS+.","Operating Systems"],["Which Linux file system is the common modern default, offering journaling for crash protection?",["ext4","NTFS","APFS","FAT16"],0,"ext4 journals changes before they happen, reducing the risk of corruption from crashes or power loss, and reliably handles large volumes and files - making it the standard choice for most Linux systems today.","Operating Systems"],["What should always happen before formatting a storage device?",["Back up any important data on it","Disconnect the device from power immediately","Rename the device","Update the device's firmware"],0,"Formatting wipes everything on a drive - files, programs, and partition data. Backing up anything important beforehand is essential since formatting cannot be undone.","Operational Procedures"],["Which installation type wipes a drive completely and installs a totally fresh copy of an OS?",["A clean install","An in-place upgrade","A zero-touch deployment","A PXE refresh"],0,"A clean install erases the existing OS and all data before installing fresh, often used to resolve serious system issues or remove unwanted software - it requires backing up data beforehand.","Operating Systems"],["Which method lets an organization install an OS on many machines over the network without physical install media?",["PXE boot","A clean install from USB","Safe Mode installation","An in-place upgrade"],0,"PXE (Preboot Execution Environment) boot lets a computer load install files from a network server rather than local media, letting IT departments deploy an OS to many machines quickly.","Operating Systems"],["What's a key limitation of MBR-style disk partitioning?",["It's capped at roughly 2TB drives and four primary partitions","It cannot be used with SSDs at all","It only supports a single partition ever","It requires UEFI firmware to function"],0,"MBR (Master Boot Record) can't address drives beyond about 2TB and allows a maximum of four primary partitions - GPT was introduced specifically to remove these limits on modern systems.","Operating Systems"],["Which deployment style installs an OS fully automatically with zero user interaction?",["Zero-touch deployment","Manual clean install","In-place upgrade","Dual-boot installation"],0,"Zero-touch deployment relies on pre-configured scripts and tools (like Microsoft MDT or WDS) to install and configure an OS without anyone answering setup prompts - ideal for large-scale rollouts.","Operating Systems"],["Why should driver compatibility be checked before upgrading an operating system?",["To make sure existing connected hardware keeps functioning","Because drivers are only relevant to printers","Because upgrading always deletes all drivers permanently","Because it's required to activate a new Windows license"],0,"Drivers let the OS talk to hardware like printers, GPUs, and network adapters. If a driver isn't compatible with the new OS version, that hardware can stop working or throw errors after the upgrade.","Software Troubleshooting"],["Which Windows edition targets large enterprises needing advanced security and device management?",["Windows Enterprise","Windows Home","Windows S Mode","Windows Starter"],0,"The Enterprise edition includes management and security tools like BitLocker, Group Policy, and advanced threat protection, aimed at IT departments managing large fleets of devices.","Operating Systems"],["What's a notable limitation of Windows S Mode?",["App installation is restricted to the Microsoft Store","It cannot connect to the internet","It has no security features at all","It only runs on tablets"],0,"S Mode locks app installs to the Microsoft Store for security and speed, which improves safety but blocks third-party applications that more advanced users may need.","Operating Systems"],["Which Windows edition adds support for the Resilient File System (ReFS)?",["Windows Pro for Workstations","Windows Home","Windows S Mode","Windows Starter"],0,"ReFS is built for high-performance, corruption-resistant workloads like large file servers and virtualization, and is available in advanced editions such as Pro for Workstations and Enterprise - not in Home.","Operating Systems"],["What's the key difference between an In-Place Upgrade and a Clean Install?",["An In-Place Upgrade keeps existing files/settings; a Clean Install erases everything","They are functionally identical processes","A Clean Install always requires a product key while an upgrade never does","An In-Place Upgrade only works on Enterprise editions"],0,"An In-Place Upgrade installs a newer Windows version while preserving personal files, apps, and settings. A Clean Install wipes the drive first, which is often used to resolve deep-seated system issues.","Operating Systems"],["Why does Windows 11 require TPM 2.0?",["It hardens security by protecting encryption keys at the hardware level","It's needed purely to display higher screen resolutions","It increases available storage space","It speeds up the boot animation only"],0,"TPM 2.0 is a hardware chip that securely stores encryption keys and sensitive data, adding a layer of protection that's much harder for attackers to bypass than software-only security - a key reason Microsoft made it mandatory.","Security"],["Which built-in Windows tool lets you monitor running apps, background processes, and control what launches at startup?",["Task Manager","File Explorer","Control Panel","Disk Cleanup"],0,"Task Manager shows real-time CPU/memory usage, running processes, and startup program impact, making it the go-to tool for closing frozen apps or trimming what launches automatically.","Operating Systems"],["What does Windows Hello primarily provide?",["Biometric sign-in using face, fingerprint, or PIN","Automatic Wi-Fi password recovery","Cloud backup of the entire hard drive","Remote desktop access by default"],0,"Windows Hello lets users log in with facial recognition, a fingerprint scan, or a secure PIN instead of a traditional password, improving both convenience and security on supported hardware.","Security"],["Which command-line tool scans a Windows drive for file system errors and bad sectors?",["Check Disk (chkdsk)","Disk Cleanup","Task Scheduler","System Restore"],0,"chkdsk scans a drive for file system errors and bad sectors, and can attempt repairs - helping maintain drive health and prevent slowdowns or data loss caused by corruption.","Operating Systems"],["A laptop is running slow with CPU usage stuck near 90%, plus frequent freezes. What two steps make sense first?",["Open Task Manager to find the top CPU consumer, then close nonessential high-usage apps","Reinstall Windows immediately and buy a new laptop","Increase the monitor's brightness and lower the volume","Disable the touchpad and restart the router"],0,"Task Manager quickly identifies which process is hogging the CPU. Closing nonessential high-usage applications often relieves the freezing and slowdown without needing deeper troubleshooting.","Software Troubleshooting"],["What does Windows Defender Firewall primarily do?",["Block unauthorized network connections while allowing trusted ones through","Physically disconnect the Ethernet cable when a threat is found","Scan printed documents for malware","Encrypt the entire hard drive"],0,"The firewall filters incoming and outgoing network traffic, blocking suspicious or unauthorized connections while letting trusted apps and services communicate normally - protecting the device without breaking legitimate software.","Security"],["What's the key difference between a domain and a workgroup?",["Domains suit centralized corporate management; workgroups suit small/home networks","A workgroup requires a dedicated server while a domain never does","Domains and workgroups are the exact same networking model","Workgroups scale better than domains for large enterprises"],0,"A domain uses a central server to manage users and devices at scale, ideal for businesses. A workgroup is simpler and decentralized, with each computer managing its own accounts - better suited to home or small networks.","Networking"],["What is a VPN primarily used for?",["Encrypting data and securing traffic over a public network","Increasing a monitor's maximum refresh rate","Speeding up a printer's queue","Automatically updating device drivers"],0,"A VPN creates an encrypted tunnel between a device and a remote server, protecting sensitive traffic especially on public Wi-Fi in places like airports or cafes where eavesdropping is a real risk.","Security"],["Which network connection type is generally the most stable and reliable?",["Wired Ethernet","Bluetooth","Public Wi-Fi hotspot","Satellite internet"],0,"Wired Ethernet avoids wireless interference and distance-related signal drop, delivering more consistent speed and lower latency - a strong reason it's preferred for gaming, streaming, and large transfers.","Networking"],["Why would someone mark a network connection as \"metered\" in Windows?",["To limit background data usage and hold back large automatic downloads","To make the connection permanently faster","To disable the firewall on that connection only","To force the connection to use Ethernet instead of Wi-Fi"],0,"Marking a connection as metered tells Windows to treat it like a limited data plan, holding back large background downloads like automatic updates - useful on mobile hotspots or capped internet plans.","Networking"],["If shared files on a network aren't showing up on another PC, what should be checked?",["Firewall rules and network discovery settings","The monitor's color calibration","The CPU's overclock settings","The printer's toner level"],0,"Missing shared files often trace back to network discovery being off, or the firewall blocking file-sharing traffic. Enabling discovery and allowing sharing through the firewall usually resolves the issue.","Networking"],["What does Windows Defender (Microsoft Defender Antivirus) protect a system against?",["Viruses, malware, and other cyber threats","Physical damage from drops","Power surges from the wall outlet","Overheating components"],0,"Microsoft Defender Antivirus runs in the background scanning files in real time, defending against viruses, spyware, ransomware, and similar threats, with regular updates from Microsoft to cover new attacks.","Security"],["Why is it recommended to use a Standard User account instead of an Admin account for daily computer use?",["It limits malware's ability to make unauthorized system changes","It makes the computer boot noticeably faster","It's required to install any software at all","It automatically encrypts all files"],0,"A Standard account can't install or modify system files without an administrator prompt, which blocks malware from silently making major changes - adding a meaningful layer of everyday protection.","Security"],["Which login method is generally considered the most secure?",["Biometrics, like Windows Hello face or fingerprint recognition","A simple 4-digit PIN","A password reused across multiple sites","No login required at all"],0,"Biometric traits like a fingerprint or face are far harder to guess, steal, or share than a password or PIN, making biometric sign-in one of the strongest common authentication methods available.","Security"],["What does BitLocker actually do?",["Encrypts the entire drive to block unauthorized access to its contents","Compresses files to save disk space","Speeds up file transfer over USB","Automatically backs up files to the cloud"],0,"BitLocker encrypts a drive's full contents, so if a laptop is lost or stolen, the data remains unreadable to anyone without the correct encryption key - especially important for portable devices.","Security"],["What's a consequence of disabling User Account Control (UAC)?",["Malware can install software without prompting for permission first","The system will refuse to boot","All installed antivirus software stops working","File Explorer becomes permanently disabled"],0,"UAC normally requires explicit approval before software can make major system changes. Turning it off removes that checkpoint, making it easier for malware to install itself silently and unnoticed.","Security"],["Which command displays a computer's current IP address, subnet mask, and default gateway?",["ipconfig","ping","chkdsk","mkdir"],0,"ipconfig prints out key network details for the local machine, making it one of the most commonly used first steps when diagnosing connectivity problems.","Operating Systems"],["What does the ping command actually check?",["Whether a device or website responds and is reachable","Whether a hard drive has bad sectors","Whether RAM is seated correctly","Whether a printer has enough toner"],0,"ping sends small test packets to a target and waits for a response, confirming basic network reachability - a fast way to check whether a device or site is actually up and responding.","Operating Systems"],["Which command permanently deletes a file from the command line, bypassing the Recycle Bin?",["del","mkdir","chkdsk","ipconfig"],0,"Unlike deleting a file through File Explorer, the del command removes it immediately with no trip through the Recycle Bin - powerful, but risky if used carelessly.","Operating Systems"],["What does chkdsk do when run on a Windows drive?",["Scans for and attempts to fix file system errors and bad sectors","Deletes temporary internet files","Displays the current IP configuration","Creates a new folder on the desktop"],0,"chkdsk examines a drive's file system for errors and bad sectors, and can attempt to repair what it finds - useful when a drive is behaving oddly or files have become inaccessible.","Operating Systems"],["Which command creates a new folder from the Windows command line?",["mkdir","del","ping","chkdsk"],0,"mkdir (or md) creates a new directory at the current location - for example, mkdir Projects creates a folder named Projects right there in the command line.","Operating Systems"],["What commonly causes a Windows system to feel sluggish overall?",["Too many programs launching automatically at startup","Having too much free disk space","Using a wired mouse instead of wireless","Having more than one monitor connected"],0,"A heavy load of startup programs consumes memory and CPU right from boot, dragging down both startup time and overall responsiveness. Disabling unnecessary ones is a common, effective fix.","Software Troubleshooting"],["What should a technician check first when troubleshooting a Blue Screen of Death (BSOD)?",["The specific error code shown on the BSOD screen","The desktop wallpaper","The monitor's brightness level","The Wi-Fi router's firmware version"],0,"The BSOD typically displays an error code pointing to the likely cause - often a driver or hardware issue. Reading that code first saves time versus guessing at the problem.","Software Troubleshooting"],["Which command can repair a corrupted boot sector in Windows?",["bootrec /fixmbr","chkdsk /f","ipconfig /release","del /boot"],0,"bootrec /fixmbr rewrites the Master Boot Record, which is essential for starting the OS. If malware or a failed update corrupts it, this command can often restore normal booting without a full reinstall.","Software Troubleshooting"],["Windows Update keeps failing on a PC. What's a reasonable first troubleshooting step?",["Clear the Windows Update cache","Reinstall the entire operating system","Replace the motherboard","Disable the network adapter permanently"],0,"Corrupted or incomplete files sitting in the update cache commonly cause repeated update failures. Clearing that cache forces Windows to redownload clean files, often resolving the issue without more drastic steps.","Software Troubleshooting"],["What typically causes an 'Operating System Not Found' error at boot?",["A damaged boot sector or missing boot configuration files","A monitor set to the wrong input","An outdated mouse driver","A printer that's offline"],0,"When the boot sector or Boot Configuration Data (BCD) is damaged or missing, the system has nothing telling it where to find the OS. Repair tools like the bootrec commands can often fix this without a full reinstall.","Software Troubleshooting"]];
